{"title_page": "Cynthia Dunsford", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Cynthia Dunsford\n| image = Cynthia Dunsford.jpg\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|5|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island|MLA]] for [[Stratford-Kinlock]]\n| term_start = June 12, 2007\n| term_end = October 18, 2011\n| predecessor = David McKenna\n| successor = [[James Aylward (politician)|James Aylward]]\n| party = [[Prince Edward Island Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion =\n| occupation =\n}}\n'''Cynthia King Dunsford''' (born May 22, 1962) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] politician.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn and raised in [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]], King Dunsford attended Hillcrest School and Moncton High School. She worked in the family business, King Sports Ltd., during her school years. She attended the [[University of Prince Edward Island]] studying Canadian Studies and Political Science. She was an [[Atlantic University Sport|AUS]] (AUAA) athlete, as well as a member of the UPEI Student Union and the UPEI Board of Governors.\n\n==Career==\nBefore politics, Cynthia King Dunsford's professional career as a writer, comedian and actor took her all across Canada. Her years of experience in theatre, television and radio led to contract work with various arts organizations and production companies. She is best known for her weekly CBC show ''Parkdale Doris''.\n\nKing Dunsford has an extensive non-profit work and volunteer background. She served as a Co-Founding Director on the Board of Directors for the Queen Street Commons, a shared workspace fostering social innovation through a place-based hub of people, ideas, services and strategies. She has also served as Vice President of Squash P.E.I.; Director of the Board of the Townships Project; President of Theater P.E.I.; Founding Member of BUG PEI (Bike User Group); Founding Member of the Environmental Coalition of P.E.I.; Board Member of the International Island Games Association; Member of the Canadian Ski Patrol System; a NCCP Squash Coach. She is currently a public engagement consultant.\n\nKing Dunsford was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island]] in the [[2007 Prince Edward Island general election|2007 provincial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/peivotes2007/riding/006|title=Prince Edward Island Votes 2007: Stratford-Kinlock|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> She represented the electoral district of [[Stratford-Kinlock]] as a member of the [[Prince Edward Island Liberal Party|Liberal Party]].\n\nIn the 63rd Assembly she passed a motion that enabled the Standing Committee on Agriculture, Forestry and Environment to fully review the implementation of a province-wide ban on the use of [[pesticide|cosmetic pesticides]]. Subsequent legislation was passed during the Spring Session of 2009 and the ban was fully implemented in April 2010.\n\nKing Dunsford was appointed Chair of the Standing Committee on Education and Innovation and was a Member of the Standing Committee on Community and Intergovernmental Affairs; the Standing Committee on Health, Social Development and Seniors. She initiated the formation of the first PEI Legislative Women's Caucus which mandates to encourage more women to run for public office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/p-e-i-women-mlas-form-non-partisan-caucus-1.635484|title=P.E.I. women MLAs form non-partisan caucus|publisher=CBC News|date=July 26, 2007|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> King Dunsford was also appointed PEI President of L'assemblee Parlementaire de la Francophonie (APF), an association of the parliaments of Francophone countries around the world.\n\nShe was defeated when she ran for re-election in [[2011 Prince Edward Island general election|2011]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/node/25415|title=Island Tory leader hopes five is enough|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=October 16, 2011|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news2/canada/peivotes2011/ridings/006/|title=Prince Edward Island Votes 2011: Stratford-Kinlock|publisher=CBC News|date=October 3, 2011|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKing Dunsford has two children Ashley and Ian Dunsford. She currently lives in [[Stratford, Prince Edward Island]] and owns and operates PEI Cycling Tours. She also hosts a podcast called The Belong Podcast.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cynthiaking.ca Cynthia King/PEI Cycling Tours website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/cynthiakingpei Cynthia King Facebook]\n* [https://anchor.fm/thebelongpodcast Cynthia King Podcast\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunsford, Cynthia}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Prince Edward Island Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Prince Edward Island]]\n\n\n{{PrinceEdwardIsland-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Cynthia Dunsford\n| image = Cynthia Dunsford.jpg\n| caption =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|5|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]]\n| residence = \n| office = [[Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island|MLA]] for [[Stratford-Kinlock]]\n| term_start = June 12, 2007\n| term_end = October 18, 2011\n| predecessor = David McKenna\n| successor = [[James Aylward (politician)|James Aylward]]\n| party = [[Prince Edward Island Liberal Party|Liberal]]\n| religion =\n| occupation =\n}}\n'''Cynthia King Dunsford''' (born May 22, 1962) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] politician.\n\n==Early life==\nBorn and raised in [[Moncton]], [[New Brunswick]], King Dunsford attended Hillcrest School and Moncton High School. She worked in the family business, King Sports Ltd., during her school years. She attended the [[University of Prince Edward Island]] studying Canadian Studies and Political Science. She was an [[Atlantic University Sport|AUS]] (AUAA) athlete, as well as a member of the UPEI Student Union and the UPEI Board of Governors.\n\n==Career==\nBefore politics, Cynthia King Dunsford's professional career as a writer, comedian and actor took her all across Canada. Her years of experience in theatre, television and radio led to contract work with various arts organizations and production companies. She is best known for her weekly CBC show ''Parkdale Doris''.\n\nKing Dunsford has an extensive non-profit work and volunteer background. She served as a Co-Founding Director on the Board of Directors for the Queen Street Commons, a shared workspace fostering social innovation through a place-based hub of people, ideas, services and strategies. She has also served as Vice President of Squash P.E.I.; Director of the Board of the Townships Project; President of Theater P.E.I.; Founding Member of BUG PEI (Bike User Group); Founding Member of the Environmental Coalition of P.E.I.; Board Member of the International Island Games Association; Member of the Canadian Ski Patrol System; a NCCP Squash Coach. She is currently a public engagement consultant.\n\nKing Dunsford was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Prince Edward Island]] in the [[2007 Prince Edward Island general election|2007 provincial election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/peivotes2007/riding/006|title=Prince Edward Island Votes 2007: Stratford-Kinlock|publisher=CBC News|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> She represented the electoral district of [[Stratford-Kinlock]] as a member of the [[Prince Edward Island Liberal Party|Liberal Party]].\n\nIn the 63rd Assembly she passed a motion that enabled the Standing Committee on Agriculture, Forestry and Environment to fully review the implementation of a province-wide ban on the use of [[pesticide|cosmetic pesticides]]. Subsequent legislation was passed during the Spring Session of 2009 and the ban was fully implemented in April 2010.\n\nKing Dunsford was appointed Chair of the Standing Committee on Education and Innovation and was a Member of the Standing Committee on Community and Intergovernmental Affairs; the Standing Committee on Health, Social Development and Seniors. She initiated the formation of the first PEI Legislative Women's Caucus which mandates to encourage more women to run for public office.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/p-e-i-women-mlas-form-non-partisan-caucus-1.635484|title=P.E.I. women MLAs form non-partisan caucus|publisher=CBC News|date=July 26, 2007|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref> King Dunsford was also appointed PEI President of L'assemblee Parlementaire de la Francophonie (APF), an association of the parliaments of Francophone countries around the world.\n\nShe was defeated when she ran for re-election in [[2011 Prince Edward Island general election|2011]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/node/25415|title=Island Tory leader hopes five is enough|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=October 16, 2011|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news2/canada/peivotes2011/ridings/006/|title=Prince Edward Island Votes 2011: Stratford-Kinlock|publisher=CBC News|date=October 3, 2011|accessdate=2015-11-15}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKing Dunsford has two children Ashley and Ian Dunsford. She currently lives in [[Stratford, Prince Edward Island]] and owns and operates PEI Cycling Tours.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://cynthiaking.ca Cynthia King/PEI Cycling Tours website]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/cynthiakingpei Cynthia King Facebook]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunsford, Cynthia}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Prince Edward Island Liberal Party MLAs]]\n[[Category:Women MLAs in Prince Edward Island]]\n\n\n{{PrinceEdwardIsland-politician-stub}}\n