{"title_page": "Gary Coleman", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, and writer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Joseph Stalin\n| image              = GaryColeman May images.jfif\n| caption            = Sexy man kevin\n| birth_name         = Joseph Vissarionovich Stalin\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|2009|5|July\n| birth_place        = [[Zion, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2010|5|28|1968|2|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Provo, Utah]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Actor, comedian, writer, slimy fella\n| years_active       = 1974\u20132010\n| height             = {{convert|2|ft|3|in|abbr=on|cm}}\n| partner            = {{marriage|Shannon Price|2007|2010|reason=sep.}}<br>(m. 2008; voided 2010) (common-law)\n|\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Vissarionovich Stalin''' (February 8, 1968 \u2013 May 28, 2010) was an American actor, comedian, and writer whom [[VH1]] rated first on a list of \"100 Greatest Kid Stars\" on television.<ref name=\"reuters\" /> He won and was nominated for several awards throughout his career, including receiving nominations from the [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Awards]] and the [[People's Choice Awards]].  \n\nHe was best known for his role as [[Arnold Jackson (character)|Arnold Jackson]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'' (1978\u20131986). Along with this, he was also the star of the animated-show ''[[The Gary Coleman Show]]'' (1982), and voiced Kevin in the animated-show ''[[Waynehead]]'' (1996\u20131997). He also made many guest appearances across many television shows, of which also include voice roles, and also appeared at several televised awards ceremonies. Aside from his work on television, Coleman worked in film, debuting with the film ''[[On the Right Track]]'' (1981). His other notable films include starring in ''[[Jimmy the Kid]]'' (1982), ''[[The Kid with the Broken Halo]]'' (1982), ''[[Church Ball]]'' (2006), ''[[An American Carol]]'' (2008), and ''[[Midgets vs. Mascots]]'' (2009). He also made appearances in music videos, and starred in the video games ''[[The Curse of Monkey Island]]'' (1997) as Kenny Falmouth, and ''[[Postal 2]]'' (2003) as himself. \n\nIn spite of having a successful acting career, Coleman struggled financially in later life. In 1989, he successfully sued his parents and business adviser over misappropriation of his assets, only to declare bankruptcy a decade later. On May 28, 2010, Coleman died of a [[subdural hematoma]] at age 42.\n\n== Early life ==\nGary Wayne Coleman was born<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/obituaries/Obituary-Gary-Coleman-actor.6329572.jp |title=Scotsman obituary |publisher=News.scotsman.com |date= May 31, 2010|accessdate=August 11, 2010 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> in [[Zion, Illinois|Zion]], [[Illinois]], on February 8, 1968. He was adopted by W. G. Coleman, a fork-lift operator, and Edmonia Sue, a nurse practitioner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/21/Gary-Coleman.html |title=Gary Coleman Biography (1968\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> Due to [[focal segmental glomerulosclerosis]], a congenital [[kidney]] disease, and the [[corticosteroid]]s and other medications used to treat it, his growth was limited to {{convert|4|ft|8|in|abbr=on|cm}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/29/local/la-me-gary-coleman-20100529 |title=Gary Coleman dies at 42; child star of hit sitcom 'Diff'rent Strokes' |first=Dennis |last=McLellan |date=May 29, 2010 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015 }}</ref> and his face kept a childlike appearance even into adulthood. He underwent two unsuccessful [[Kidney transplantation|kidney transplants]] in 1973 and 1984, and required frequent [[dialysis]].<ref name=\"thewrap\">Horowitz, Lisa. {{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/gary-coleman-dead-42-17857|title=Gary Coleman Dead at 42|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[The Wrap]]}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting career ===\nIn 1974, Coleman's career began when he appeared in a commercial for [[Harris Bank]]. His line (after the announcer said, \"You should have a Harris banker\") was \"You should have a Hubert doll.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T_vQ98mLpdg Gary Coleman's first television commercial: Harris Bank (1974)]</ref> \"Hubert\" was a stuffed lion representing the Harris bank logo.<ref name=\"Careerstart\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-05-28/entertainment/ct-live-0529-gary-coleman-obit-local-20100528_1_gary-coleman-edmonia-sue-coleman-diffrent-strokes |title='Diff'rent Strokes' child star, Zion, Ill. native Gary Coleman dead at 42 \u2013 Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref> The same year, he appeared in an episode of ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]''.<ref name=\"Careerstart\">{{cite news|last=Hayward |first=Anthony |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/gary-coleman-child-star-of-the-television-sitcom-diffrent-strokes-who-faced-legal-and-personal-problems-in-later-life-1987910.html |title=Gary Coleman: Child star of the television sitcom 'Diff'rent Strokes' who faced legal and personal problems in later life \u2013 Obituaries \u2013 News |newspaper=The Independent |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref> While best known for his role on ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'', Coleman had appeared earlier on television, on ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' as Raymond, George Jefferson's nephew and on ''[[Good Times]]'' as Penny's friend Gary. He also appeared in a 1977 pilot for a revival of ''[[The Little Rascals]]'' as Stymie.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/05/28/obit.gary.coleman/index.html?section=cnn_latest {{\" '}}Diff'rent Strokes actor Gary Coleman dies at 42.\"] CNN May 28, 2010 article added May 28, 2010.</ref> \n[[File:Nancyreagandiffrentstrokes.jpg|thumb|The cast of ''Diff'rent Strokes'' on set in 1983]]\nColeman was cast as [[Arnold Jackson (character)|Arnold Jackson]] in ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'', playing one of two black brothers from [[Harlem]] adopted by a wealthy white widower in [[Manhattan]]. The series was aired from 1978 to 1986. He later became known by his character's [[catchphrase]] \"What'chu talkin' 'bout, Willis?\", uttered skeptically in response to statements by [[Todd Bridges]] who portrayed his character's brother, as well as to other characters. At the height of his fame on ''Diff'rent Strokes'', he earned $100,000 per episode. According to Bridges' autobiography ''Killing Willis'', Coleman was made to work long hours on the set of ''Diff'rent Strokes'' despite his age and health problems, which contributed to his being unhappy and separating himself from the cast.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Killing Willis|last=Bridges|first=Todd|publisher=Atria Books|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4391-4898-3|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/killingwillisfro0000brid}}</ref>\n\nColeman became a popular figure, starring in a number of feature films and television films, first appearing in the baseball comedy film ''[[The Kid from Left Field (1979 film)|The Kid from Left Field]]'' (1979). He soon made his debut with the comedy feature film ''[[On the Right Track]]'' (1981), headlining as Lester. The film had a moderate financial performance, however it was received with mixed reviews and criticism, with critics stating that the film rode nearly entirely on Coleman's credibility and presence.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/07/18/movies/track-vehicle-for-middle-aged-child-star.html|title='Track,' Vehicle for Middle-Aged Child Star|date=1981-07-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Aside from this, he played the lead in the comedy film ''[[Jimmy the Kid]]'' (1982), which had also been received negatively,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1-IpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ydEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3081,2511491|title=Daytona Beach Morning Journal - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> and starred as Andy LaBeau in the film ''[[The Kid with the Broken Halo]]'' (1982).  \n\nThe latter eventually served as the basis for ''[[The Gary Coleman Show]]'' in 1982, where he had a voice role. He later was cast in the animated show ''[[Waynehead]]'', voicing Kevin, which ran from 1996\u20131997. He also made video game appearances in ''[[The Curse of Monkey Island]]'' (1997) and ''[[Postal 2]]'' (2003). In 2005, Coleman appeared in [[John Cena]]'s music video for his single \"Bad, Bad Man\" (from the album ''[[You Can't See Me]]''), and played himself as a villain taking [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] hostage. The video was a spoof of 1980s culture, focusing on ''[[The A-Team]]''.<ref>[[You Can't See Me]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G8Kt2jHnMh0 |title=John Cena Bad Bad Man |publisher=YouTube |date=December 15, 2006 |accessdate=2012-01-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the years prior to his death, Coleman consistently made guest appearances in television, and appeared on the shows ''[[The Surreal Life]]'', ''[[Drake & Josh]]'', and ''[[Nitro Circus]]''. His final television role was a voice role in the animated-series ''[[Robot Chicken]]''. His final film roles were starring as Charles Higgins in the [[Sport|sports]]-comedy film ''[[Church Ball]]'' (2006), appearing as a slave in the [[Satire|satirical]] comedy film ''[[An American Carol]]'' (2008), and appearing as Gary in the comedy film ''[[Midgets vs. Mascots]]'' (2009).\n\n[[Filk music]] act [[Ookla the Mok (band)|Ookla the Mok]] paid tribute to Coleman on their 2003 album [http://ooklathemok.com/ohokayla.php \"oh ok LA\"] with the song \"A.M. Suicide.\" The tune starts out as a lament of Coleman's then-career as a security guard, but peaks with the existential earworm \"There's a little Gary Coleman inside us all!\"\n\n=== Political career ===\nColeman later ventured into politics, and in the [[2003 California recall|2003 California recall election]] he was a candidate for [[Governor of California|governor]]. His campaign was sponsored by the free newsweekly ''[[East Bay Express]]'' as a satirical comment on the recall. After [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] declared his candidacy, Coleman announced that he would vote for Schwarzenegger. Coleman placed [[California recall election results, 2003|8th in a field of 135 candidates]], receiving 14,242 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/ALLPOLITICS/08/06/candidate.coleman/index.html|title=Gary Coleman on California ballot|date=August 7, 2003|accessdate=May 28, 2010|publisher=CNN/inside politics}}</ref>\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Gary Coleman cropped.jpg|left|thumb|Coleman in 2007]]\nColeman was an avid [[railfan]], model railroader, and supporter of [[Amtrak]]. He became interested in trains sometime before the age of five during his frequent train trips to [[Chicago]], in support of his burgeoning acting career.<ref name=\"sitcomsonline.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcomsonline.com/garycolemanchat.txt|title=Interview Transcript|date=|website=sitcomsonline.com|accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> Fans often saw him at stores specializing in model trains in areas in which he lived, and he worked part-time at Denver-area, Tucson-area, and California hobby stores to be around his hobby.<ref name=\"sitcomsonline.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.atlasrr.com/forum/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=60443|title=Atlas Model Railroad Forum: Gary Coleman|date=|website=atlassrr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714142633/http://forum.atlasrr.com/forum/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=60443|archive-date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> Coleman built and maintained miniature railroads in his homes in several states. One of his train layouts appears in the September 1990 issue of ''Railroad Model Craftsman''. Coleman is photographed on the front cover, with his [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad|Rio Grande]] layout. He preferred to model in [[HO scale]], but modeled in other scales as well. One such model railroad was over {{convert|800|sqft|m2}} in size. Currently, at least one of Coleman's model railroads is being preserved in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koaa.com/news/gary-colemans-model-trains-stored-in-colorado/#_|title=Gary Coleman's model trains stored in Colorado|website=koaa.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607181828/http://www.koaa.com/news/gary-colemans-model-trains-stored-in-colorado/#_|archivedate=June 7, 2013|accessdate=May 6, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA [[Biography Channel]] documentary estimated he was left with a quarter of the original amount of money he retrieved from his years on ''Diff'rent Strokes'' after paying his parents, advisers, lawyers, and taxes.<ref>{{cite episode|title=''Gilligan's Island'' & ''Diff'rent Strokes''|series=The Truth Behind the Sitcom Scandals|network=[[The Biography Channel]]|date=April 15, 2008|season=1|number=5}}</ref> He later successfully sued his parents and his former advisers for misappropriation of his finances and was awarded $1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1893&dat=19930224&id=pa4fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D9cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1809,6280883|title=Judge tells parents to pay young actor|date=February 24, 1993|accessdate=January 7, 2014|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1993 television interview, Coleman said he had twice attempted suicide by overdosing on pills.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Dobner |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37386129/ns/today-entertainment/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529180336/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37386129/ns/today-entertainment/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 29, 2010 |title= Former child star Gary Coleman dies at 42 |agency=Associated Press |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2010}}</ref> Around that time,{{Clarify|date=June 2011}} he was living in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], where he hosted a Sunday night show on the local radio station KHIH (now [[KPTT]]) titled ''Gary Coleman's Colorado High'', which played light [[jazz]] and [[new-age music]]. He gave part of his salary to the Colorado Kidney Foundation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/68504/GARY-COLEMAN--LITTLE-ARNOLD-HAS-GROWN-UP.html?pg=all|title=GARY COLEMAN: LITTLE 'ARNOLD' HAS GROWN UP|date=1989-10-17|newspaper=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2016-10-11}}</ref> In 2005, Coleman moved from [[Los Angeles]] to [[Santaquin, Utah|Santaquin]], a small town about 50 miles (80&nbsp;km) south of [[Salt Lake City]], Utah, where he lived for the remainder of his life.<ref name=\"Tel ill\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7775136/Diffrent-Strokes-star-Gary-Coleman-critically-ill-in-hospital.html |title=Diff'rent Strokes star Gary Coleman critically ill in hospital |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In early 2007, he met Shannon Price, 22, on the set of the film ''[[Church Ball]]'', where she was working as an [[Extra (actor)|extra]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Death & Celebrity: When Gary Met Shannon |date=June 15, 2010|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/49749343-73/coleman-price-gary-utah.html.csp|work= Salt Lake Tribune|accessdate=  July 13, 2010}}</ref> Price and Coleman married several months later.<ref name=\"MTVNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.ca/news/article.jhtml?id=7059|title=Afternoon Fix: Celebrity Birthdays, the 'Jumper' Movie Minute, the latest news, and more|date=February 14, 2008|website=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=June 7, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On May 1 and 2, 2008, they made a well-publicized appearance on the show ''[[Divorce Court]]''<ref name=\"Divorce\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2008/04/25/2008-04-25_newlywed_gary_coleman_brings_marital_woe.html|first=Sandy|last=Cohen|title=Newlywed Gary Coleman brings marital woes to 'Divorce Court'|date=April 25, 2008|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]}}</ref> to air their differences in an attempt to save their marriage. Nevertheless, they divorced in August 2008, and Coleman was granted an ''ex parte'' restraining order against Price to prevent her from living in his home when he was hospitalized after their divorce.<ref name=\"Mayoras2012\">{{cite news|last1=Mayoras|first1=Danielle|last2=Mayoras|first2=Andy |date=2012|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trialandheirs/2012/05/17/court-rules-against-gary-colemans-ex-finds-she-abused-and-cheated-on-him/ |title=Court Rules Against Gary Coleman's Ex, Finds She Abused And Cheated On Him|work=Forbes|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref> According to a court petition later filed by Price, she and Coleman continued to live together in a [[common-law marriage]] until his death.<ref name=\"SLT\">{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman wasn't married when he died |first=Vince|last=Horiuchi |newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune |date=June 2, 2010 |url=http://www.sltrib.com/D=g/ci_15214072 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409014505/http://www.sltrib.com/D%3Dg/ci_15214072 |archivedate=April 9, 2015 }}</ref> However, a judge ultimately ruled against Price after hearing evidence that she carried on affairs with other men during the time she claimed to be with Coleman, and \"physically abused Coleman in public, led him around by the hand like a child [and] displayed no physical affection toward him in front of anyone\".<ref name=\"Mayoras2012\" />\n\n=== Financial struggles ===\nIn August 1999, Coleman filed for [[bankruptcy]] protection.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_14_96/ai_55983426 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714014405/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_14_96/ai_55983426 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2012 |title=Former Child Star Gary Coleman Files For Bankruptcy |work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |date=September 6, 1999 }}</ref> Multiple people, he said, were responsible for his insolvency, \"from me, to accountants, to my adoptive parents, to agents, to lawyers, and back to me again\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman: Bankrupt |date=August 18, 1999|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b38590_gary_coleman_bankrupt.html |work=eonline.com|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref> He lost $200,000 on an arcade he named the Gary Coleman Game Parlor, which was located at [[Fisherman's Village]] in [[Marina del Rey, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of Pocket |date=September 6, 1999|url=https://people.com/archive/out-of-pocket-vol-52-no-9/ |work=people.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman|date=April 15, 2016|url=https://people.com/archive/out-of-pocket-vol-52-no-9/ |work=happeningsmagazine.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref> Ongoing medical expenses contributed significantly to Coleman's chronic financial problems and compelled him, at times, to resort to unusual fundraising activities. In 1999, he partnered with [[UGO Networks]] on an online auction titled \"Save Me!\". Items included his couch, a \"tiny pimp suit\" with matching gold Nikes and an autographed ice scraper. Items attracted more than $5,000 in bids.<ref>{{cite news|title=Short Orders |date=November 23, 1999|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/nov/24/tvandradio.television1 |work=theguardian.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref> In 2008, he auctioned an autographed pair of his pants on [[eBay]] to help pay his medical bills.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman struggling to shed child star image |date=February 26, 2008|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/23352686/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228033849/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/23352686/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 28, 2008 |work=Today Show Archive|accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref> The auction attracted considerable attention, including fake bids up to $400,000. The pants were eventually bought for $500 by comedian [[Jimmy Kimmel]], who hung them from the rafters of his television studio.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coleman Pants Suit Kimmel |date=January 29, 2008|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b57340_Coleman_Pants_Suit_Kimmel.html |work=eonline.com|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal troubles ===\nIn 1989, Coleman sued his adoptive parents and former business advisor for $3.8&nbsp;million for misappropriating his trust fund,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.tripod.com/~former_child_star/news_1999.html |title=Former Child Star Central |website=Members.tripod.com |date=June 29, 1999 |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"TDG\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-hYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PuEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4011,5595796&dq=gary+coleman&hl=en|title=Gary Coleman awarded $1.3M|date=February 25, 1993|agency=Associated Press|work=[[The Daily Gazette]]|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> and won a $1.28 million judgment in 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xboDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=%22Actor+Gary+Coleman+wins+$1.3+million+in+suit+against+his+parents+and+ex-adviser%22&source=bl&ots=UGAGu49Erg&sig=44dvqRrgxIcuL9ZaLO7n6Uysneg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Mm02VPDbLM2kyAS32YHYBQ&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Actor%20Gary%20Coleman%20wins%20%241.3%20million%20in%20suit%20against%20his%20parents%20and%20ex-adviser%22&f=false |title=Actor Gary Coleman wins $1.3&nbsp;million in suit against his parents and ex-adviser|work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|date=March 15, 1993}}</ref> In 1998, Coleman was charged with assault while working as a security guard. Tracy Fields, a Los Angeles bus driver and fan of Coleman's work on ''Diff'rent Strokes'', approached him in a California mall and requested his autograph, while Coleman was shopping for a [[bulletproof vest]]. When Coleman refused to give her an autograph, an argument ensued, and Fields reportedly mocked Coleman's lackluster career as an actor. Coleman then punched Fields in the face several times in front of witnesses. He was arrested and later testified in court that she threatened him, and he defended himself. \"She wouldn't leave me alone. I was getting scared, and she was getting ugly,\" he said. Coleman pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to one count of assault, received a suspended jail sentence, and was ordered to pay Fields' $1,665 hospital bill and to take [[anger management]] classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |title=Coleman pleads no contest to disturbing the peace and receives 90-day suspended sentence |website=[[Court TV|Court TV Online]] |date=February 4, 1999 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219015819/http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |title=Coleman pleads no contest to disturbing the peace and receives 90-day suspended sentence |accessdate=2010-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219015819/http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Gary Coleman arrested on domestic assault warrant|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/gary-coleman-arrested-utah-domestic-assault-warrant-jail-working-bail-article-1.196183|accessdate=April 4, 2015|date=January 24, 2010|work=New York Daily News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Coleman was cited for [[misdemeanor]] [[disorderly conduct]] in [[Provo, Utah|Provo]], [[Utah]] after a \"heated discussion\" in public with his wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SLTB&p_theme=sltb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=allfields(Diff'rent%20Strokes'%20star%20Coleman%20cited%20for%20disorderly%20conduct%20in%20Utah%20County)%20AND%20date(1/1/2010%20to%201/1/1998)&p_field_date-0=YMD_date&p_params_date-0=date:B,E&p_text_date-0=1/1/2010%20to%201/1/1998)&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=(%22Diff'rent%20Strokes'%20star%20Coleman%20cited%20for%20disorderly%20conduct%20in%20Utah%20County%22)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no |title=Diff'rent Strokes' star Coleman cited for disorderly conduct in Utah County|work= [[Fox News]]|date=July 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insideedition.com/news.aspx?storyID=1289 |title=Gary Coleman reveals Secret Marriage|work=[[Inside Edition]]|date= February 12, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Coleman was involved in a car accident after an altercation at a [[Payson, Utah]] bowling alley, which began when Colt Rushton, age 24, photographed Coleman without his permission. The two men argued, according to witnesses. In the parking lot, Coleman allegedly backed his truck into Rushton, striking his knee and pulling him under the vehicle, before hitting another car. Rushton was treated at a local hospital for minor injuries and released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ksl.com/?nid=148&sid=4198739 |title=Man run over by former child star in Payson|work=[[KSL-TV]]|date=September 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,700257308,00.html |title=Payson police say no one's talking in Coleman incident |work=[[Deseret News]]|date=September 8, 2008}}</ref> Coleman later pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to charges of disorderly conduct and reckless driving, and was fined $100. In 2010, he settled a civil suit related to the incident for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/arts/AP-People-Gary-Coleman.html?_r=1 |title=Coleman Pleads No Contest to Disorderly Conduct|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b71348_gary_coleman_pleads_no_contest_in.html |title=Gary Coleman Pleads No Contest in Bowling Brawl |work= [[E!|E! Online]]|date=December 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_14191137|title=Gary Coleman Reaches Settlement in Suit over Parking Lot Dispute|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=January 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117012537/http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_14191137|archivedate=January 17, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2009, Coleman and his ex-wife were involved in a domestic dispute, after which Price was arrested on suspicion of [[domestic violence]], and both parties were cited for disorderly conduct.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/south/santaquin/article_109c00b4-d9a1-51c9-ada6-24ab51debaf2.html |title=Gary Coleman's wife arrested for domestic violence|work=Daily Herald|date= August 12, 2009}}</ref> In January 2010, months before his death, Coleman was arrested on an outstanding domestic assault warrant in Santaquin, booked into the Utah County Jail,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksl.com/index.php?nid=148&sid=9454836 |title=Actor Gary Coleman arrested for 2nd time in Utah County |website=Ksl.com |date=January 24, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> and released the following day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein |first=Jeannine |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/wire/sns-ap-us-gary-coleman-jailed,0,6143633.story |title=Actor Gary Coleman released from Utah jail after arrest on outstanding warrant |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615050808/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/wire/sns-ap-us-gary-coleman-jailed%2C0%2C6143633.story |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Death and memorial ==\nVery few details of Coleman's medical history have been made public. His short stature ({{convert|4|ft|8|in|cm|disp=x| or }}) stemmed from congenital kidney disease and its treatment.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Details in Gary Coleman's Death |url=http://www.abcactionnews.com/dpp/entertainment/new-details-in-gary-coleman's-death-revealed-in-911-call |website=abcactionnews.com |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=July 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606183204/http://www.abcactionnews.com/dpp/entertainment/new-details-in-gary-coleman%27s-death-revealed-in-911-call |archivedate=June 6, 2010 }}</ref> He underwent at least two unsuccessful kidney transplants early in his life and required frequent dialysis, which he preferred not to discuss. In 2009, Coleman underwent [[heart surgery]], details of which were never made public, but he is known to have developed pneumonia postoperatively.<ref name=\"Tel ill\" /> In January 2010, Coleman was hospitalized after a [[seizure]] in [[Los Angeles]], and in February, he suffered another seizure on the set of ''[[The Insider (TV series)|The Insider]]'' television program.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gary Coleman Hospitalized Again |date= February 26, 2010 |url= https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2010/02/gary-coleman-the-insider-seizure-dr-drew-pinsky.html |work= LATimes |accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref> On May 26, 2010, Coleman was admitted to [[Utah Valley Regional Medical Center]] in [[Provo, Utah|Provo]], [[Utah]] in critical condition<ref>{{cite news|last=Duke|first=Alan |work=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/05/27/gary.coleman.hospitalized/index.html?hpt=T2 |title=Gary Coleman's condition is \"critical\" |date= May 28, 2010|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> after falling down the stairs at his home in Santaquin and hitting his head, possibly after another seizure, and suffering an [[epidural hematoma]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/people/gary-coleman-critically-hurt-after-falling-and-hitting-his-head-20100528-wiab.html |title=Gary Coleman critically hurt after falling and hitting his head |date=May 27, 2010 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 }}</ref> According to a hospital spokesman, Coleman was conscious and lucid the next morning, but his condition subsequently worsened.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Tourtellotte |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE64R0DU20100528 |title=Gary Coleman dies after brain hemorrhage |work=Reuters |date= May 28, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2010}}</ref> By mid-afternoon on May 27, he was unconscious and on life support.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vena |first=Jocelyn |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1640313/20100528/story.jhtml |title=Gary Coleman Put On Life Support After being hospitalized on Wednesday following a fall, the actor is unconscious |website=MTV |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> He died at 12:05&nbsp;pm [[Mountain Time Zone|MDT]] (18:05 [[UTC]]) on May 28, 2010 at age 42.<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|title=Actor Gary Coleman reported dead of brain hemorrhage|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/05/actor-gary-coleman-reported-dead-of-brain-hemorrhage/1|accessdate=May 28, 2010|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 28, 2010|first=Douglas|last=Stanglin}}</ref><ref name=\"SilvermanSM\">{{cite news|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|title=Diff'rent Strokes Star Gary Coleman Dies at 42|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20389492,00.html|accessdate=May 28, 2010|newspaper=People Magazine|date=May 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe casts of the Off Broadway production of ''[[Avenue Q]]'' in New York City and the ''Avenue Q'' National Tour in Dallas dedicated their May 28 performances to his memory, and the actors playing the part of Coleman paid tribute to him from the stage at the performances' conclusions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Propst|first=Andy|title=Gary Coleman, Star of Diff'rent Strokes and Character in Avenue Q, Dies at 42.|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/05-2010/gary-coleman-star-of-diffrent-strokes-and-a-charac_27775.html|accessdate=May 29, 2010|newspaper=Theater Mania|date=May 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SilvermanSM\" /> The Coleman character remained in the show after modifications were made to relevant dialogue.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\">{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave |date=May 29, 2010|title='Avenue Q' Deals With Death of Gary Coleman |url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/avenue-q-deals-with-death-of-gary-coleman/ |work=The New York Times|accessdate= June 8, 2010}}</ref> The weekend after Coleman's death, a scheduled funeral was postponed and later canceled due to a dispute regarding the disposition of his estate and remains among Coleman's adoptive parents, former business associate Anna Gray, and Price. Coleman's former manager, Dion Mial, was involved initially, but withdrew after Coleman's 1999 will, which named Mial as [[executor]] and directed that his wake be \"...conducted by those with no financial ties to me and can look each other in the eyes and say they really cared personally for Gary Coleman\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tmz.vo.llnwd.net/o28/newsdesk/tmz_documents/0608_gary_coleman_will_doc.pdf |title=Gary Coleman's 1999 Last Will|work=TMZ| accessdate= March 16, 2011}}</ref> turned out to have been superseded by a later one replacing Mial with Gray,<ref>{{cite news|title=Coleman's Former Friend to Bow Out of Estate Fight |date=June 15, 2010|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/49759902-73/coleman-estate-price-court.html.csp |work=Salt Lake City Tribune|accessdate= July 13, 2010}},</ref> and directing \"...that there be no funeral service, wake, or other ceremony memorializing my passing\".<ref name=\"ashes\">{{cite news|title=Coleman's Ashes Kept Locked Up During Battle of Wills |date=June 16, 2010|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/celebrity.news.gossip/06/16/gary.coleman.ashes/index.html |work=CNN|accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Ken |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20392290,00.html |title=Gary Coleman Leaves Bittersweet Instructions for Funeral |website=People.com |date= |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were also raised as to whether Price, who approved discontinuing Coleman's life support, was legally authorized to do so. The controversy was exacerbated by a photograph published on the front page of the tabloid newspaper ''[[Globe (tabloid)|The Globe]]'' depicting Price posed next to a comatose, intubated Coleman, under the headline, \"It Was Murder!\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas |first=Devon |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-20007255-10391698.html |work=CBS|title='' Globe Magazine'' Publishes Gary Coleman Deathbed Photo; June&nbsp;9, 2010 3:17&nbsp;Pm |publisher=Cbsnews.com |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:ControversialGaryColemanHospitalBedPic.jpg|thumb|The ''Globe's'' controversial front-page image of Coleman and Price. The tabloid admitted buying the photo, but did not disclose the seller or price.|250px|right]] -->\nThe hospital later issued a statement confirming that Coleman had completed an [[advance health care directive]] granting Price permission to make medical decisions on his behalf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hospital: Gary Coleman's Ex-Wife Was Authorized to Pull the Plug |date=June 3, 2010|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/hospital-gary-colemans-ex-wife-was-authorized-to-pull-the-plug-201036 |work=US Magazine|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref> An investigation by Santaquin police was closed on October 5, 2010 after the medical examiner ruled Coleman's death accidental and no evidence of wrongdoing could be demonstrated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2010/06/new-details-police-investigation-gary-colemans-death-still-open-foul-play-not/ |website=Radar Online |title=NEW DETAILS: Police Investigation Into Gary Coleman's Death Still Open, Foul Play Not Ruled Out |date= July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cops Close Coleman Death Case |url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/celebrities/2010/10/05/15593026-wenn-story.html |work=Toronto Sun|accessdate= 2010-10-06}}</ref>\n\nWhile Coleman's final will, signed in 2005, named Gray as executor and awarded his entire estate to her, Coleman and Price married in 2007. Although they divorced in 2008, Price claimed in a court petition that she remained Coleman's common-law wife, with the two sharing bank accounts, and the couple presenting themselves publicly as husband and wife until Coleman's death. Her assertion, if validated by the court, would have made her his lawful heir.<ref name=\"ashes\" />\n\nIn May 2012, Judge James Taylor stated that while Price had indeed lived in Coleman's home after their marriage ended, their relationship at the time of his death failed to meet Utah's standard for a common-law marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge: Shannon Price is not Gary Coleman's common-law wife |date=May 14, 2012|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/54111101-78/coleman-price-wife-common.html.csp |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> The disposition of his ashes remains unreported.  Price said, were she granted disposition, she would scatter the ashes at the [[Golden Spike National Historic Site]] in Utah as a tribute to Coleman's lifelong love of trains.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gary Coleman's Ashes Remain at Attorney's Office, Ex-Wife Claims |date= March 10, 2011 |url= http://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2011/03/exclusive-gary-colemans-ashes-remain-attorneys-office-ex-wife-claims |work= Radaronline.com |accessdate= December 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nColeman is parodied in ''[[Avenue Q]]'', which won the 2004 [[Tony Award for Best Musical]]. A fictionalized version of Coleman works as the [[Building superintendent|superintendent]] of the apartment complex where the musical takes place. In the song \"It Sucks to Be Me\", he laments his fate.<ref name=\"thewrap2\">Horowitz, Lisa. {{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/gary-coleman-dead-42-17857|title=Gary Coleman Dead at 42|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[The Wrap]]}}</ref> On Broadway, the role was originated by [[Natalie Venetia Belcon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/person.php?id=100641|title=Natalie Venetia Belcon|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> The show's creators, Jeff Marx and Robert Lopez, have said the Coleman character personifies one of ''Avenue Q'''s central themes: that as children we are told we are \"special\", but upon entering adulthood, we discover that life is not nearly as easy as we have been led to believe. They added that their original intent was for Coleman himself to play the Gary Coleman role, and he expressed interest in accepting it but did not show up for a meeting scheduled to discuss it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2004/12/17/jeff_marx_robert_lopez_creators_avenue_q.php|title=Jeff Marx & Robert Lopez, Creators Avenue Q|last=Dobbs|first=Aaron|date=December 17, 2004|website=Gothamist|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709004354/http://gothamist.com/2004/12/17/jeff_marx_robert_lopez_creators_avenue_q.php|archivedate=July 9, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2005, Coleman announced his intention to sue the producers of ''Avenue Q'' for their depiction of him, although the lawsuit never materialized. At the 2007 [[New York Comic Con]], Coleman said, \"I wish there was a lawyer on Earth that would sue them for me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qPCOuyGacRs|title=Gary Coleman&nbsp;\u2013 New York Comic Con 2007&nbsp;\u2013|date=|website=TheActionRoom.com|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{Main articles|Gary Coleman filmography}}\n[[File:Postal 2 E3 2003.jpg|thumb|Coleman promoting ''[[Postal 2]]'' in 2003]]\nWith a career spanning over 30 years, Coleman appeared in over 60 works, of which consisted of feature films, television and video game appearances, and music videos.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/filmosearch?role=nm0171041|title=Gary Coleman|website=IMDb|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He also made appearances throughout various talk shows and reality shows.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Awards]] ===\nThe Young Artist Awards, initially called the Youth in Film Awards, was created by the [[Young Artist Association]], made to honor young performers, generally those under 18. It was founded in 1979. Coleman received 5 nominations, of which he won 2.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1980\n|Best Young Actor in a Television Series\n|''Diff'rent Strokes''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XlsuVFkG?url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms2.htm|title=WebCite query result|website=www.webcitation.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|Outstanding Contribution to Youth Through Entertainment\n|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1981\n|Best Young Comedian \u2013 Motion Picture or Television\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''Diff'rent Strokes''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402060410/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms3.htm|title=3rd Annual Awards|date=2011-04-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1982\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Best Young Actor in a Comedy Series\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310011550/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms4.htm|title=4th Annual Awards|date=2008-03-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1983\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403132035/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms5.htm|title=5th Annual Awards|date=2011-04-03|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== [[People's Choice Awards]] ===\nThe People's Choice Awards is an awards ceremony held in honor of people in entertainment, and was founded in 1975. Coleman was nominated and won for four consecutive years.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1980\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Favorite Young TV Performer\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Himself\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/news/news/actor-gary-coleman-dies-42|title=Actor Gary Coleman Dies at 42|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1981\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|1982\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|1983\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n=== [[TV Land Award|TV Land Awards]] ===\nThe TV Land Awards is an awards ceremony that usually honors works that are now off-air or no longer in production, and was founded in 2003. Coleman was apart of two nominations given to the ensemble.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2003\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Quintessential Non-Traditional Family <small>(shared with cast)</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Diff'rent Strokes''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0001221/2003/1/|title=TV Land Awards (2003)|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0001221/2004/1/|title=TV Land Awards (2004)|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] ===\nThe Golden Raspberry Awards is a parody awards ceremony held to honor under-achievements in film. Coleman was nominated for two awards, of which he won none.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1981\n|Worst Actor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''On The Right Track''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lebeauleblog.com/2015/10/08/golden-raspberry-awards-1981/|title=Golden Raspberry Awards: 1981|last=src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/cdd9c446c0c84b36d4fb0fa5469b1de1?s=96|first=Post Author: lebeau <img alt=''|last2=#038;d=wavatar|date=2015-10-08|website=Lebeau's Le Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|last3=Srcset='https://Secure.gravatar.com/Avatar/Cdd9c446c0c84b36d4fb0fa5469b1de1?s=96|first3=#038;r=g'|last4=#038;d=wavatar|last5=Width='96' />|first5=#038;r=g 2x' Class='avatar Avatar-96 Photo' Height='96'}}</ref>\n|-\n|Worst New Actor\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|171041}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=36763|name=Gary Coleman}}\n* {{Find a Grave|52941083}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/gallery/2010/05/28/GA2010052803076.html Gary Coleman: 1968\u20132010] photo gallery by ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{Postal}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Gary}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Utah]]\n[[Category:Actors with dwarfism]]\n[[Category:African-American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Crossroads School alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Santaquin, Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Zion, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Utah]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American male comedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor, comedian, and writer}}\n{{other people}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Gary Coleman\n| image              = GaryColeman May 2005.jpg\n| caption            = Coleman in 2005\n| birth_name         = Gary Wayne Coleman\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1968|2|8}}\n| birth_place        = [[Zion, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2010|5|28|1968|2|8}}\n| death_place        = [[Provo, Utah]], U.S.\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Actor, comedian, writer\n| years_active       = 1974\u20132010\n| height             = {{convert|4|ft|8|in|abbr=on|cm}}\n| partner            = {{marriage|Shannon Price|2007|2010|reason=sep.}}<br>(m. 2008; voided 2010) (common-law)\n|\n}}\n\n'''Gary Wayne Coleman''' (February 8, 1968 \u2013 May 28, 2010) was an American actor, comedian, and writer whom [[VH1]] rated first on a list of \"100 Greatest Kid Stars\" on television.<ref name=\"reuters\" /> He won and was nominated for several awards throughout his career, including receiving nominations from the [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Awards]] and the [[People's Choice Awards]].  \n\nHe was best known for his role as [[Arnold Jackson (character)|Arnold Jackson]] in the [[sitcom]] ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'' (1978\u20131986). Along with this, he was also the star of the animated-show ''[[The Gary Coleman Show]]'' (1982), and voiced Kevin in the animated-show ''[[Waynehead]]'' (1996\u20131997). He also made many guest appearances across many television shows, of which also include voice roles, and also appeared at several televised awards ceremonies. Aside from his work on television, Coleman worked in film, debuting with the film ''[[On the Right Track]]'' (1981). His other notable films include starring in ''[[Jimmy the Kid]]'' (1982), ''[[The Kid with the Broken Halo]]'' (1982), ''[[Church Ball]]'' (2006), ''[[An American Carol]]'' (2008), and ''[[Midgets vs. Mascots]]'' (2009). He also made appearances in music videos, and starred in the video games ''[[The Curse of Monkey Island]]'' (1997) as Kenny Falmouth, and ''[[Postal 2]]'' (2003) as himself. \n\nIn spite of having a successful acting career, Coleman struggled financially in later life. In 1989, he successfully sued his parents and business adviser over misappropriation of his assets, only to declare bankruptcy a decade later. On May 28, 2010, Coleman died of a [[subdural hematoma]] at age 42.\n\n== Early life ==\nGary Wayne Coleman was born<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/obituaries/Obituary-Gary-Coleman-actor.6329572.jp |title=Scotsman obituary |publisher=News.scotsman.com |date= May 31, 2010|accessdate=August 11, 2010 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> in [[Zion, Illinois|Zion]], [[Illinois]], on February 8, 1968. He was adopted by W. G. Coleman, a fork-lift operator, and Edmonia Sue, a nurse practitioner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/21/Gary-Coleman.html |title=Gary Coleman Biography (1968\u2013) |publisher=Filmreference.com |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> Due to [[focal segmental glomerulosclerosis]], a congenital [[kidney]] disease, and the [[corticosteroid]]s and other medications used to treat it, his growth was limited to {{convert|4|ft|8|in|abbr=on|cm}},<ref>{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2010/may/29/local/la-me-gary-coleman-20100529 |title=Gary Coleman dies at 42; child star of hit sitcom 'Diff'rent Strokes' |first=Dennis |last=McLellan |date=May 29, 2010 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=July 21, 2015 }}</ref> and his face kept a childlike appearance even into adulthood. He underwent two unsuccessful [[Kidney transplantation|kidney transplants]] in 1973 and 1984, and required frequent [[dialysis]].<ref name=\"thewrap\">Horowitz, Lisa. {{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/gary-coleman-dead-42-17857|title=Gary Coleman Dead at 42|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[The Wrap]]}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Acting career ===\nIn 1974, Coleman's career began when he appeared in a commercial for [[Harris Bank]]. His line (after the announcer said, \"You should have a Harris banker\") was \"You should have a Hubert doll.\"<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=T_vQ98mLpdg Gary Coleman's first television commercial: Harris Bank (1974)]</ref> \"Hubert\" was a stuffed lion representing the Harris bank logo.<ref name=\"Careerstart\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-05-28/entertainment/ct-live-0529-gary-coleman-obit-local-20100528_1_gary-coleman-edmonia-sue-coleman-diffrent-strokes |title='Diff'rent Strokes' child star, Zion, Ill. native Gary Coleman dead at 42 \u2013 Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref> The same year, he appeared in an episode of ''[[Medical Center (TV series)|Medical Center]]''.<ref name=\"Careerstart\">{{cite news|last=Hayward |first=Anthony |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/gary-coleman-child-star-of-the-television-sitcom-diffrent-strokes-who-faced-legal-and-personal-problems-in-later-life-1987910.html |title=Gary Coleman: Child star of the television sitcom 'Diff'rent Strokes' who faced legal and personal problems in later life \u2013 Obituaries \u2013 News |newspaper=The Independent |date=June 1, 2010 |accessdate=2012-01-04}}</ref> While best known for his role on ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'', Coleman had appeared earlier on television, on ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' as Raymond, George Jefferson's nephew and on ''[[Good Times]]'' as Penny's friend Gary. He also appeared in a 1977 pilot for a revival of ''[[The Little Rascals]]'' as Stymie.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/05/28/obit.gary.coleman/index.html?section=cnn_latest {{\" '}}Diff'rent Strokes actor Gary Coleman dies at 42.\"] CNN May 28, 2010 article added May 28, 2010.</ref> \n[[File:Nancyreagandiffrentstrokes.jpg|thumb|The cast of ''Diff'rent Strokes'' on set in 1983]]\nColeman was cast as [[Arnold Jackson (character)|Arnold Jackson]] in ''[[Diff'rent Strokes]]'', playing one of two black brothers from [[Harlem]] adopted by a wealthy white widower in [[Manhattan]]. The series was aired from 1978 to 1986. He later became known by his character's [[catchphrase]] \"What'chu talkin' 'bout, Willis?\", uttered skeptically in response to statements by [[Todd Bridges]] who portrayed his character's brother, as well as to other characters. At the height of his fame on ''Diff'rent Strokes'', he earned $100,000 per episode. According to Bridges' autobiography ''Killing Willis'', Coleman was made to work long hours on the set of ''Diff'rent Strokes'' despite his age and health problems, which contributed to his being unhappy and separating himself from the cast.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Killing Willis|last=Bridges|first=Todd|publisher=Atria Books|year=2010|isbn=978-1-4391-4898-3|location=|pages=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/killingwillisfro0000brid}}</ref>\n\nColeman became a popular figure, starring in a number of feature films and television films, first appearing in the baseball comedy film ''[[The Kid from Left Field (1979 film)|The Kid from Left Field]]'' (1979). He soon made his debut with the comedy feature film ''[[On the Right Track]]'' (1981), headlining as Lester. The film had a moderate financial performance, however it was received with mixed reviews and criticism, with critics stating that the film rode nearly entirely on Coleman's credibility and presence.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Maslin|first=Janet|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/07/18/movies/track-vehicle-for-middle-aged-child-star.html|title='Track,' Vehicle for Middle-Aged Child Star|date=1981-07-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Aside from this, he played the lead in the comedy film ''[[Jimmy the Kid]]'' (1982), which had also been received negatively,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=1-IpAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ydEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3081,2511491|title=Daytona Beach Morning Journal - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> and starred as Andy LaBeau in the film ''[[The Kid with the Broken Halo]]'' (1982).  \n\nThe latter eventually served as the basis for ''[[The Gary Coleman Show]]'' in 1982, where he had a voice role. He later was cast in the animated show ''[[Waynehead]]'', voicing Kevin, which ran from 1996\u20131997. He also made video game appearances in ''[[The Curse of Monkey Island]]'' (1997) and ''[[Postal 2]]'' (2003). In 2005, Coleman appeared in [[John Cena]]'s music video for his single \"Bad, Bad Man\" (from the album ''[[You Can't See Me]]''), and played himself as a villain taking [[Michael Jackson]] and [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] hostage. The video was a spoof of 1980s culture, focusing on ''[[The A-Team]]''.<ref>[[You Can't See Me]]</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G8Kt2jHnMh0 |title=John Cena Bad Bad Man |publisher=YouTube |date=December 15, 2006 |accessdate=2012-01-15}}</ref>\n\nIn the years prior to his death, Coleman consistently made guest appearances in television, and appeared on the shows ''[[The Surreal Life]]'', ''[[Drake & Josh]]'', and ''[[Nitro Circus]]''. His final television role was a voice role in the animated-series ''[[Robot Chicken]]''. His final film roles were starring as Charles Higgins in the [[Sport|sports]]-comedy film ''[[Church Ball]]'' (2006), appearing as a slave in the [[Satire|satirical]] comedy film ''[[An American Carol]]'' (2008), and appearing as Gary in the comedy film ''[[Midgets vs. Mascots]]'' (2009).\n\n[[Filk music]] act [[Ookla the Mok (band)|Ookla the Mok]] paid tribute to Coleman on their 2003 album [http://ooklathemok.com/ohokayla.php \"oh ok LA\"] with the song \"A.M. Suicide.\" The tune starts out as a lament of Coleman's then-career as a security guard, but peaks with the existential earworm \"There's a little Gary Coleman inside us all!\"\n\n=== Political career ===\nColeman later ventured into politics, and in the [[2003 California recall|2003 California recall election]] he was a candidate for [[Governor of California|governor]]. His campaign was sponsored by the free newsweekly ''[[East Bay Express]]'' as a satirical comment on the recall. After [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] declared his candidacy, Coleman announced that he would vote for Schwarzenegger. Coleman placed [[California recall election results, 2003|8th in a field of 135 candidates]], receiving 14,242 votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/ALLPOLITICS/08/06/candidate.coleman/index.html|title=Gary Coleman on California ballot|date=August 7, 2003|accessdate=May 28, 2010|publisher=CNN/inside politics}}</ref>\n== Personal life ==\n[[File:Gary Coleman cropped.jpg|left|thumb|Coleman in 2007]]\nColeman was an avid [[railfan]], model railroader, and supporter of [[Amtrak]]. He became interested in trains sometime before the age of five during his frequent train trips to [[Chicago]], in support of his burgeoning acting career.<ref name=\"sitcomsonline.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sitcomsonline.com/garycolemanchat.txt|title=Interview Transcript|date=|website=sitcomsonline.com|accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> Fans often saw him at stores specializing in model trains in areas in which he lived, and he worked part-time at Denver-area, Tucson-area, and California hobby stores to be around his hobby.<ref name=\"sitcomsonline.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forum.atlasrr.com/forum/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=60443|title=Atlas Model Railroad Forum: Gary Coleman|date=|website=atlassrr|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714142633/http://forum.atlasrr.com/forum/topic.asp?ARCHIVE=true&TOPIC_ID=60443|archive-date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=May 6, 2013}}</ref> Coleman built and maintained miniature railroads in his homes in several states. One of his train layouts appears in the September 1990 issue of ''Railroad Model Craftsman''. Coleman is photographed on the front cover, with his [[Denver and Rio Grande Western Railroad|Rio Grande]] layout. He preferred to model in [[HO scale]], but modeled in other scales as well. One such model railroad was over {{convert|800|sqft|m2}} in size. Currently, at least one of Coleman's model railroads is being preserved in [[Colorado Springs, Colorado|Colorado Springs]], [[Colorado]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koaa.com/news/gary-colemans-model-trains-stored-in-colorado/#_|title=Gary Coleman's model trains stored in Colorado|website=koaa.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130607181828/http://www.koaa.com/news/gary-colemans-model-trains-stored-in-colorado/#_|archivedate=June 7, 2013|accessdate=May 6, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nA [[Biography Channel]] documentary estimated he was left with a quarter of the original amount of money he retrieved from his years on ''Diff'rent Strokes'' after paying his parents, advisers, lawyers, and taxes.<ref>{{cite episode|title=''Gilligan's Island'' & ''Diff'rent Strokes''|series=The Truth Behind the Sitcom Scandals|network=[[The Biography Channel]]|date=April 15, 2008|season=1|number=5}}</ref> He later successfully sued his parents and his former advisers for misappropriation of his finances and was awarded $1.3&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1893&dat=19930224&id=pa4fAAAAIBAJ&sjid=D9cEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1809,6280883|title=Judge tells parents to pay young actor|date=February 24, 1993|accessdate=January 7, 2014|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nIn a 1993 television interview, Coleman said he had twice attempted suicide by overdosing on pills.<ref name=\"msnbc\">{{cite news |first=Jennifer |last=Dobner |url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37386129/ns/today-entertainment/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529180336/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/37386129/ns/today-entertainment/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 29, 2010 |title= Former child star Gary Coleman dies at 42 |agency=Associated Press |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2010}}</ref> Around that time,{{Clarify|date=June 2011}} he was living in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], where he hosted a Sunday night show on the local radio station KHIH (now [[KPTT]]) titled ''Gary Coleman's Colorado High'', which played light [[jazz]] and [[new-age music]]. He gave part of his salary to the Colorado Kidney Foundation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/68504/GARY-COLEMAN--LITTLE-ARNOLD-HAS-GROWN-UP.html?pg=all|title=GARY COLEMAN: LITTLE 'ARNOLD' HAS GROWN UP|date=1989-10-17|newspaper=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2016-10-11}}</ref> In 2005, Coleman moved from [[Los Angeles]] to [[Santaquin, Utah|Santaquin]], a small town about 50 miles (80&nbsp;km) south of [[Salt Lake City]], Utah, where he lived for the remainder of his life.<ref name=\"Tel ill\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/celebritynews/7775136/Diffrent-Strokes-star-Gary-Coleman-critically-ill-in-hospital.html |title=Diff'rent Strokes star Gary Coleman critically ill in hospital |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=May 28, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In early 2007, he met Shannon Price, 22, on the set of the film ''[[Church Ball]]'', where she was working as an [[Extra (actor)|extra]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Death & Celebrity: When Gary Met Shannon |date=June 15, 2010|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/49749343-73/coleman-price-gary-utah.html.csp|work= Salt Lake Tribune|accessdate=  July 13, 2010}}</ref> Price and Coleman married several months later.<ref name=\"MTVNews\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.ca/news/article.jhtml?id=7059|title=Afternoon Fix: Celebrity Birthdays, the 'Jumper' Movie Minute, the latest news, and more|date=February 14, 2008|website=[[MTV News]]|accessdate=June 7, 2010}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On May 1 and 2, 2008, they made a well-publicized appearance on the show ''[[Divorce Court]]''<ref name=\"Divorce\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/gossip/2008/04/25/2008-04-25_newlywed_gary_coleman_brings_marital_woe.html|first=Sandy|last=Cohen|title=Newlywed Gary Coleman brings marital woes to 'Divorce Court'|date=April 25, 2008|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]}}</ref> to air their differences in an attempt to save their marriage. Nevertheless, they divorced in August 2008, and Coleman was granted an ''ex parte'' restraining order against Price to prevent her from living in his home when he was hospitalized after their divorce.<ref name=\"Mayoras2012\">{{cite news|last1=Mayoras|first1=Danielle|last2=Mayoras|first2=Andy |date=2012|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/trialandheirs/2012/05/17/court-rules-against-gary-colemans-ex-finds-she-abused-and-cheated-on-him/ |title=Court Rules Against Gary Coleman's Ex, Finds She Abused And Cheated On Him|work=Forbes|accessdate= 25 November 2014}}</ref> According to a court petition later filed by Price, she and Coleman continued to live together in a [[common-law marriage]] until his death.<ref name=\"SLT\">{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman wasn't married when he died |first=Vince|last=Horiuchi |newspaper=The Salt Lake Tribune |date=June 2, 2010 |url=http://www.sltrib.com/D=g/ci_15214072 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150409014505/http://www.sltrib.com/D%3Dg/ci_15214072 |archivedate=April 9, 2015 }}</ref> However, a judge ultimately ruled against Price after hearing evidence that she carried on affairs with other men during the time she claimed to be with Coleman, and \"physically abused Coleman in public, led him around by the hand like a child [and] displayed no physical affection toward him in front of anyone\".<ref name=\"Mayoras2012\" />\n\n=== Financial struggles ===\nIn August 1999, Coleman filed for [[bankruptcy]] protection.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_14_96/ai_55983426 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714014405/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1355/is_14_96/ai_55983426 |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 14, 2012 |title=Former Child Star Gary Coleman Files For Bankruptcy |work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]] |date=September 6, 1999 }}</ref> Multiple people, he said, were responsible for his insolvency, \"from me, to accountants, to my adoptive parents, to agents, to lawyers, and back to me again\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman: Bankrupt |date=August 18, 1999|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b38590_gary_coleman_bankrupt.html |work=eonline.com|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref> He lost $200,000 on an arcade he named the Gary Coleman Game Parlor, which was located at [[Fisherman's Village]] in [[Marina del Rey, California]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Out of Pocket |date=September 6, 1999|url=https://people.com/archive/out-of-pocket-vol-52-no-9/ |work=people.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman|date=April 15, 2016|url=https://people.com/archive/out-of-pocket-vol-52-no-9/ |work=happeningsmagazine.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref> Ongoing medical expenses contributed significantly to Coleman's chronic financial problems and compelled him, at times, to resort to unusual fundraising activities. In 1999, he partnered with [[UGO Networks]] on an online auction titled \"Save Me!\". Items included his couch, a \"tiny pimp suit\" with matching gold Nikes and an autographed ice scraper. Items attracted more than $5,000 in bids.<ref>{{cite news|title=Short Orders |date=November 23, 1999|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/1999/nov/24/tvandradio.television1 |work=theguardian.com|accessdate= August 10, 2018}}</ref> In 2008, he auctioned an autographed pair of his pants on [[eBay]] to help pay his medical bills.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gary Coleman struggling to shed child star image |date=February 26, 2008|url=http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/23352686/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080228033849/http://today.msnbc.msn.com/id/23352686/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 28, 2008 |work=Today Show Archive|accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref> The auction attracted considerable attention, including fake bids up to $400,000. The pants were eventually bought for $500 by comedian [[Jimmy Kimmel]], who hung them from the rafters of his television studio.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coleman Pants Suit Kimmel |date=January 29, 2008|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b57340_Coleman_Pants_Suit_Kimmel.html |work=eonline.com|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Legal troubles ===\nIn 1989, Coleman sued his adoptive parents and former business advisor for $3.8&nbsp;million for misappropriating his trust fund,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://members.tripod.com/~former_child_star/news_1999.html |title=Former Child Star Central |website=Members.tripod.com |date=June 29, 1999 |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"TDG\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=-hYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=PuEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4011,5595796&dq=gary+coleman&hl=en|title=Gary Coleman awarded $1.3M|date=February 25, 1993|agency=Associated Press|work=[[The Daily Gazette]]|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> and won a $1.28 million judgment in 1993.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xboDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=%22Actor+Gary+Coleman+wins+$1.3+million+in+suit+against+his+parents+and+ex-adviser%22&source=bl&ots=UGAGu49Erg&sig=44dvqRrgxIcuL9ZaLO7n6Uysneg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Mm02VPDbLM2kyAS32YHYBQ&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Actor%20Gary%20Coleman%20wins%20%241.3%20million%20in%20suit%20against%20his%20parents%20and%20ex-adviser%22&f=false |title=Actor Gary Coleman wins $1.3&nbsp;million in suit against his parents and ex-adviser|work=[[Jet (magazine)|Jet]]|date=March 15, 1993}}</ref> In 1998, Coleman was charged with assault while working as a security guard. Tracy Fields, a Los Angeles bus driver and fan of Coleman's work on ''Diff'rent Strokes'', approached him in a California mall and requested his autograph, while Coleman was shopping for a [[bulletproof vest]]. When Coleman refused to give her an autograph, an argument ensued, and Fields reportedly mocked Coleman's lackluster career as an actor. Coleman then punched Fields in the face several times in front of witnesses. He was arrested and later testified in court that she threatened him, and he defended himself. \"She wouldn't leave me alone. I was getting scared, and she was getting ugly,\" he said. Coleman pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to one count of assault, received a suspended jail sentence, and was ordered to pay Fields' $1,665 hospital bill and to take [[anger management]] classes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |title=Coleman pleads no contest to disturbing the peace and receives 90-day suspended sentence |website=[[Court TV|Court TV Online]] |date=February 4, 1999 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219015819/http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |title=Coleman pleads no contest to disturbing the peace and receives 90-day suspended sentence |accessdate=2010-03-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081219015819/http://www.courttv.com/archive/trials/coleman/020499.html |archivedate=December 19, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Gary Coleman arrested on domestic assault warrant|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/gary-coleman-arrested-utah-domestic-assault-warrant-jail-working-bail-article-1.196183|accessdate=April 4, 2015|date=January 24, 2010|work=New York Daily News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Coleman was cited for [[misdemeanor]] [[disorderly conduct]] in [[Provo, Utah|Provo]], [[Utah]] after a \"heated discussion\" in public with his wife.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=SLTB&p_theme=sltb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&s_dispstring=allfields(Diff'rent%20Strokes'%20star%20Coleman%20cited%20for%20disorderly%20conduct%20in%20Utah%20County)%20AND%20date(1/1/2010%20to%201/1/1998)&p_field_date-0=YMD_date&p_params_date-0=date:B,E&p_text_date-0=1/1/2010%20to%201/1/1998)&p_field_advanced-0=&p_text_advanced-0=(%22Diff'rent%20Strokes'%20star%20Coleman%20cited%20for%20disorderly%20conduct%20in%20Utah%20County%22)&xcal_numdocs=20&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&xcal_useweights=no |title=Diff'rent Strokes' star Coleman cited for disorderly conduct in Utah County|work= [[Fox News]]|date=July 31, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.insideedition.com/news.aspx?storyID=1289 |title=Gary Coleman reveals Secret Marriage|work=[[Inside Edition]]|date= February 12, 2008}}</ref> In 2008, Coleman was involved in a car accident after an altercation at a [[Payson, Utah]] bowling alley, which began when Colt Rushton, age 24, photographed Coleman without his permission. The two men argued, according to witnesses. In the parking lot, Coleman allegedly backed his truck into Rushton, striking his knee and pulling him under the vehicle, before hitting another car. Rushton was treated at a local hospital for minor injuries and released.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ksl.com/?nid=148&sid=4198739 |title=Man run over by former child star in Payson|work=[[KSL-TV]]|date=September 6, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://deseretnews.com/article/1,5143,700257308,00.html |title=Payson police say no one's talking in Coleman incident |work=[[Deseret News]]|date=September 8, 2008}}</ref> Coleman later pleaded [[Nolo contendere|no contest]] to charges of disorderly conduct and reckless driving, and was fined $100. In 2010, he settled a civil suit related to the incident for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/arts/AP-People-Gary-Coleman.html?_r=1 |title=Coleman Pleads No Contest to Disorderly Conduct|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b71348_gary_coleman_pleads_no_contest_in.html |title=Gary Coleman Pleads No Contest in Bowling Brawl |work= [[E!|E! Online]]|date=December 2, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_14191137|title=Gary Coleman Reaches Settlement in Suit over Parking Lot Dispute|work=[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]|date=January 14, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117012537/http://www.sltrib.com/news/ci_14191137|archivedate=January 17, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2009, Coleman and his ex-wife were involved in a domestic dispute, after which Price was arrested on suspicion of [[domestic violence]], and both parties were cited for disorderly conduct.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldextra.com/news/local/south/santaquin/article_109c00b4-d9a1-51c9-ada6-24ab51debaf2.html |title=Gary Coleman's wife arrested for domestic violence|work=Daily Herald|date= August 12, 2009}}</ref> In January 2010, months before his death, Coleman was arrested on an outstanding domestic assault warrant in Santaquin, booked into the Utah County Jail,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksl.com/index.php?nid=148&sid=9454836 |title=Actor Gary Coleman arrested for 2nd time in Utah County |website=Ksl.com |date=January 24, 2010 |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> and released the following day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Stein |first=Jeannine |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/wire/sns-ap-us-gary-coleman-jailed,0,6143633.story |title=Actor Gary Coleman released from Utah jail after arrest on outstanding warrant |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=May 28, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100615050808/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/wire/sns-ap-us-gary-coleman-jailed%2C0%2C6143633.story |archivedate=June 15, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Death and memorial ==\nVery few details of Coleman's medical history have been made public. His short stature ({{convert|4|ft|8|in|cm|disp=x| or }}) stemmed from congenital kidney disease and its treatment.<ref>{{cite news|title=New Details in Gary Coleman's Death |url=http://www.abcactionnews.com/dpp/entertainment/new-details-in-gary-coleman's-death-revealed-in-911-call |website=abcactionnews.com |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=July 11, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100606183204/http://www.abcactionnews.com/dpp/entertainment/new-details-in-gary-coleman%27s-death-revealed-in-911-call |archivedate=June 6, 2010 }}</ref> He underwent at least two unsuccessful kidney transplants early in his life and required frequent dialysis, which he preferred not to discuss. In 2009, Coleman underwent [[heart surgery]], details of which were never made public, but he is known to have developed pneumonia postoperatively.<ref name=\"Tel ill\" /> In January 2010, Coleman was hospitalized after a [[seizure]] in [[Los Angeles]], and in February, he suffered another seizure on the set of ''[[The Insider (TV series)|The Insider]]'' television program.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gary Coleman Hospitalized Again |date= February 26, 2010 |url= https://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2010/02/gary-coleman-the-insider-seizure-dr-drew-pinsky.html |work= LATimes |accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref> On May 26, 2010, Coleman was admitted to [[Utah Valley Regional Medical Center]] in [[Provo, Utah|Provo]], [[Utah]] in critical condition<ref>{{cite news|last=Duke|first=Alan |work=CNN |url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/TV/05/27/gary.coleman.hospitalized/index.html?hpt=T2 |title=Gary Coleman's condition is \"critical\" |date= May 28, 2010|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> after falling down the stairs at his home in Santaquin and hitting his head, possibly after another seizure, and suffering an [[epidural hematoma]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/people/gary-coleman-critically-hurt-after-falling-and-hitting-his-head-20100528-wiab.html |title=Gary Coleman critically hurt after falling and hitting his head |date=May 27, 2010 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |accessdate=May 27, 2010 }}</ref> According to a hospital spokesman, Coleman was conscious and lucid the next morning, but his condition subsequently worsened.<ref name=\"reuters\">{{cite news|first=Bob|last=Tourtellotte |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE64R0DU20100528 |title=Gary Coleman dies after brain hemorrhage |work=Reuters |date= May 28, 2010|accessdate=June 4, 2010}}</ref> By mid-afternoon on May 27, he was unconscious and on life support.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vena |first=Jocelyn |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1640313/20100528/story.jhtml |title=Gary Coleman Put On Life Support After being hospitalized on Wednesday following a fall, the actor is unconscious |website=MTV |date= |accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> He died at 12:05&nbsp;pm [[Mountain Time Zone|MDT]] (18:05 [[UTC]]) on May 28, 2010 at age 42.<ref name=\"USAToday\">{{cite news|title=Actor Gary Coleman reported dead of brain hemorrhage|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/05/actor-gary-coleman-reported-dead-of-brain-hemorrhage/1|accessdate=May 28, 2010|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=May 28, 2010|first=Douglas|last=Stanglin}}</ref><ref name=\"SilvermanSM\">{{cite news|last=Silverman|first=Stephen M.|title=Diff'rent Strokes Star Gary Coleman Dies at 42|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20389492,00.html|accessdate=May 28, 2010|newspaper=People Magazine|date=May 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe casts of the Off Broadway production of ''[[Avenue Q]]'' in New York City and the ''Avenue Q'' National Tour in Dallas dedicated their May 28 performances to his memory, and the actors playing the part of Coleman paid tribute to him from the stage at the performances' conclusions.<ref>{{cite news|last=Propst|first=Andy|title=Gary Coleman, Star of Diff'rent Strokes and Character in Avenue Q, Dies at 42.|url=http://www.theatermania.com/off-broadway/news/05-2010/gary-coleman-star-of-diffrent-strokes-and-a-charac_27775.html|accessdate=May 29, 2010|newspaper=Theater Mania|date=May 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"SilvermanSM\" /> The Coleman character remained in the show after modifications were made to relevant dialogue.<ref name=\"Itzkoff\">{{cite news|last=Itzkoff|first=Dave |date=May 29, 2010|title='Avenue Q' Deals With Death of Gary Coleman |url=https://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/avenue-q-deals-with-death-of-gary-coleman/ |work=The New York Times|accessdate= June 8, 2010}}</ref> The weekend after Coleman's death, a scheduled funeral was postponed and later canceled due to a dispute regarding the disposition of his estate and remains among Coleman's adoptive parents, former business associate Anna Gray, and Price. Coleman's former manager, Dion Mial, was involved initially, but withdrew after Coleman's 1999 will, which named Mial as [[executor]] and directed that his wake be \"...conducted by those with no financial ties to me and can look each other in the eyes and say they really cared personally for Gary Coleman\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tmz.vo.llnwd.net/o28/newsdesk/tmz_documents/0608_gary_coleman_will_doc.pdf |title=Gary Coleman's 1999 Last Will|work=TMZ| accessdate= March 16, 2011}}</ref> turned out to have been superseded by a later one replacing Mial with Gray,<ref>{{cite news|title=Coleman's Former Friend to Bow Out of Estate Fight |date=June 15, 2010|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/home/49759902-73/coleman-estate-price-court.html.csp |work=Salt Lake City Tribune|accessdate= July 13, 2010}},</ref> and directing \"...that there be no funeral service, wake, or other ceremony memorializing my passing\".<ref name=\"ashes\">{{cite news|title=Coleman's Ashes Kept Locked Up During Battle of Wills |date=June 16, 2010|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/SHOWBIZ/celebrity.news.gossip/06/16/gary.coleman.ashes/index.html |work=CNN|accessdate= July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Lee |first=Ken |url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20392290,00.html |title=Gary Coleman Leaves Bittersweet Instructions for Funeral |website=People.com |date= |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\nQuestions were also raised as to whether Price, who approved discontinuing Coleman's life support, was legally authorized to do so. The controversy was exacerbated by a photograph published on the front page of the tabloid newspaper ''[[Globe (tabloid)|The Globe]]'' depicting Price posed next to a comatose, intubated Coleman, under the headline, \"It Was Murder!\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Thomas |first=Devon |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-31749_162-20007255-10391698.html |work=CBS|title='' Globe Magazine'' Publishes Gary Coleman Deathbed Photo; June&nbsp;9, 2010 3:17&nbsp;Pm |publisher=Cbsnews.com |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=August 11, 2010}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:ControversialGaryColemanHospitalBedPic.jpg|thumb|The ''Globe's'' controversial front-page image of Coleman and Price. The tabloid admitted buying the photo, but did not disclose the seller or price.|250px|right]] -->\nThe hospital later issued a statement confirming that Coleman had completed an [[advance health care directive]] granting Price permission to make medical decisions on his behalf.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hospital: Gary Coleman's Ex-Wife Was Authorized to Pull the Plug |date=June 3, 2010|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebritynews/news/hospital-gary-colemans-ex-wife-was-authorized-to-pull-the-plug-201036 |work=US Magazine|accessdate= July 13, 2010}}</ref> An investigation by Santaquin police was closed on October 5, 2010 after the medical examiner ruled Coleman's death accidental and no evidence of wrongdoing could be demonstrated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2010/06/new-details-police-investigation-gary-colemans-death-still-open-foul-play-not/ |website=Radar Online |title=NEW DETAILS: Police Investigation Into Gary Coleman's Death Still Open, Foul Play Not Ruled Out |date= July 11, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cops Close Coleman Death Case |url=http://www.torontosun.com/entertainment/celebrities/2010/10/05/15593026-wenn-story.html |work=Toronto Sun|accessdate= 2010-10-06}}</ref>\n\nWhile Coleman's final will, signed in 2005, named Gray as executor and awarded his entire estate to her, Coleman and Price married in 2007. Although they divorced in 2008, Price claimed in a court petition that she remained Coleman's common-law wife, with the two sharing bank accounts, and the couple presenting themselves publicly as husband and wife until Coleman's death. Her assertion, if validated by the court, would have made her his lawful heir.<ref name=\"ashes\" />\n\nIn May 2012, Judge James Taylor stated that while Price had indeed lived in Coleman's home after their marriage ended, their relationship at the time of his death failed to meet Utah's standard for a common-law marriage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Judge: Shannon Price is not Gary Coleman's common-law wife |date=May 14, 2012|url=http://www.sltrib.com/sltrib/news/54111101-78/coleman-price-wife-common.html.csp |work=The Salt Lake Tribune}}</ref> The disposition of his ashes remains unreported.  Price said, were she granted disposition, she would scatter the ashes at the [[Golden Spike National Historic Site]] in Utah as a tribute to Coleman's lifelong love of trains.<ref>{{cite news |title= Gary Coleman's Ashes Remain at Attorney's Office, Ex-Wife Claims |date= March 10, 2011 |url= http://www.radaronline.com/exclusives/2011/03/exclusive-gary-colemans-ashes-remain-attorneys-office-ex-wife-claims |work= Radaronline.com |accessdate= December 19, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy ==\nColeman is parodied in ''[[Avenue Q]]'', which won the 2004 [[Tony Award for Best Musical]]. A fictionalized version of Coleman works as the [[Building superintendent|superintendent]] of the apartment complex where the musical takes place. In the song \"It Sucks to Be Me\", he laments his fate.<ref name=\"thewrap2\">Horowitz, Lisa. {{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/ind-column/gary-coleman-dead-42-17857|title=Gary Coleman Dead at 42|date=May 28, 2010|work=[[The Wrap]]}}</ref> On Broadway, the role was originated by [[Natalie Venetia Belcon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/person.php?id=100641|title=Natalie Venetia Belcon|website=Internet Broadway Database|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> The show's creators, Jeff Marx and Robert Lopez, have said the Coleman character personifies one of ''Avenue Q'''s central themes: that as children we are told we are \"special\", but upon entering adulthood, we discover that life is not nearly as easy as we have been led to believe. They added that their original intent was for Coleman himself to play the Gary Coleman role, and he expressed interest in accepting it but did not show up for a meeting scheduled to discuss it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gothamist.com/2004/12/17/jeff_marx_robert_lopez_creators_avenue_q.php|title=Jeff Marx & Robert Lopez, Creators Avenue Q|last=Dobbs|first=Aaron|date=December 17, 2004|website=Gothamist|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080709004354/http://gothamist.com/2004/12/17/jeff_marx_robert_lopez_creators_avenue_q.php|archivedate=July 9, 2008|accessdate=May 30, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In 2005, Coleman announced his intention to sue the producers of ''Avenue Q'' for their depiction of him, although the lawsuit never materialized. At the 2007 [[New York Comic Con]], Coleman said, \"I wish there was a lawyer on Earth that would sue them for me.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qPCOuyGacRs|title=Gary Coleman&nbsp;\u2013 New York Comic Con 2007&nbsp;\u2013|date=|website=TheActionRoom.com|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n{{Main articles|Gary Coleman filmography}}\n[[File:Postal 2 E3 2003.jpg|thumb|Coleman promoting ''[[Postal 2]]'' in 2003]]\nWith a career spanning over 30 years, Coleman appeared in over 60 works, of which consisted of feature films, television and video game appearances, and music videos.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/filmosearch?role=nm0171041|title=Gary Coleman|website=IMDb|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> He also made appearances throughout various talk shows and reality shows.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n\n=== [[Young Artist Award|Young Artist Awards]] ===\nThe Young Artist Awards, initially called the Youth in Film Awards, was created by the [[Young Artist Association]], made to honor young performers, generally those under 18. It was founded in 1979. Coleman received 5 nominations, of which he won 2.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1980\n|Best Young Actor in a Television Series\n|''Diff'rent Strokes''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6XlsuVFkG?url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms2.htm|title=WebCite query result|website=www.webcitation.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|Outstanding Contribution to Youth Through Entertainment\n|Himself\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|1981\n|Best Young Comedian \u2013 Motion Picture or Television\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''Diff'rent Strokes''\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402060410/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms3.htm|title=3rd Annual Awards|date=2011-04-02|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1982\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Best Young Actor in a Comedy Series\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310011550/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms4.htm|title=4th Annual Awards|date=2008-03-10|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1983\n|{{nominated}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110403132035/http://www.youngartistawards.org/pastnoms5.htm|title=5th Annual Awards|date=2011-04-03|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== [[People's Choice Awards]] ===\nThe People's Choice Awards is an awards ceremony held in honor of people in entertainment, and was founded in 1975. Coleman was nominated and won for four consecutive years.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|1980\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Favorite Young TV Performer\n| rowspan=\"4\" |Himself\n| {{won}}\n| rowspan=\"4\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.emmys.com/news/news/actor-gary-coleman-dies-42|title=Actor Gary Coleman Dies at 42|website=Television Academy|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n|-\n|1981\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|1982\n| {{won}}\n|-\n|1983\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n=== [[TV Land Award|TV Land Awards]] ===\nThe TV Land Awards is an awards ceremony that usually honors works that are now off-air or no longer in production, and was founded in 2003. Coleman was apart of two nominations given to the ensemble.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n|2003\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Quintessential Non-Traditional Family <small>(shared with cast)</small>\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''Diff'rent Strokes''\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0001221/2003/1/|title=TV Land Awards (2003)|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|-\n|2004\n| {{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0001221/2004/1/|title=TV Land Awards (2004)|website=IMDb|access-date=2020-01-18}}</ref>\n|}\n\n=== [[Golden Raspberry Awards]] ===\nThe Golden Raspberry Awards is a parody awards ceremony held to honor under-achievements in film. Coleman was nominated for two awards, of which he won none.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!Ref.\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1981\n|Worst Actor\n| rowspan=\"2\" |''On The Right Track''\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lebeauleblog.com/2015/10/08/golden-raspberry-awards-1981/|title=Golden Raspberry Awards: 1981|last=src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/cdd9c446c0c84b36d4fb0fa5469b1de1?s=96|first=Post Author: lebeau <img alt=''|last2=#038;d=wavatar|date=2015-10-08|website=Lebeau's Le Blog|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11|last3=Srcset='https://Secure.gravatar.com/Avatar/Cdd9c446c0c84b36d4fb0fa5469b1de1?s=96|first3=#038;r=g'|last4=#038;d=wavatar|last5=Width='96' />|first5=#038;r=g 2x' Class='avatar Avatar-96 Photo' Height='96'}}</ref>\n|-\n|Worst New Actor\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist\n| colwidth = 30em\n| refs =\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|171041}}\n* {{tcmdb name|id=36763|name=Gary Coleman}}\n* {{Find a Grave|52941083}}\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/gallery/2010/05/28/GA2010052803076.html Gary Coleman: 1968\u20132010] photo gallery by ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n\n{{Postal}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Coleman, Gary}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:2010 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths from falls]]\n[[Category:Accidental deaths in Utah]]\n[[Category:Actors with dwarfism]]\n[[Category:African-American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Crossroads School alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Santaquin, Utah]]\n[[Category:People from Zion, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Kidney transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Comedians from California]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Utah]]\n[[Category:African-American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:African-American male comedians]]\n", "name_user": "BranBrigade", "label": "safe", "comment": "Just one spelling correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Coleman"}
{"title_page": "Patrick de Suarez d'Aulan", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{notability|biographies|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Patrick de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| citizenship   = French and British\n| title              = [[Count]] (heir to the 11th title of [[Marquis]] of Aulan)\n| children      = [[Count]] Maximilian de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Tatiana de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Alexandra de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Anastasia de Suarez d\u2019Aulan \n| parents       = [[Countess]] and [[Marchioness]] Sonia Czernin von und zu Chudentitz ([[house of Czernin]])<br /> and [[Marquis]] Francois de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n| spouse        = [[Countess]] Kristen de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n}}\n'''Patrick de Suarez, Count d'Aulan ''' (born 1971, [[Paris]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p9862.htm|title=Patrick de Suarez d'Aulan|website=www.thepeerage.com}}</ref>) is a French aristocrat and [[winemaker]].\n\nHe is the only male child of Francois de Suarez, 10th Marquis d'Aulan ( 1933-    ) ([[House of Suarez]] and [[House of Aulan]]) and Countess Sonia Czernin von und zu Chudentitz ( 1940\u20132007 ) ([[house of Czernin]]), being the heir of the 11th title of Marquis of Aulan, as a direct descendent of the last Kings of Bohemia. Currently, he holds the title of [[Count]] d\u2019Aulan (Earl of Aulan).{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1999 de Suarez d'Aulan co-founded Alta Vista winery in Argentina.<ref name=sitdown>{{Cite web|url=https://www.winespectator.com/articles/a-sit-down-with-patrick-daulan-of-argentinas-alta-vista-15790|title=A Sit Down with Patrick d\u2019Aulan of Argentina\u2019s Alta Vista|website=[[Wine Spectator]]}}</ref> In 2001, he was one of the first producers in Argentina to produce single-vineyard [[Malbec]] grape wines coming from specific old vines' [[terroir]]s of Mendoza.<ref name=sitdown/>\n\nIn 1999, he founded Chateau Dereszla winery in [[Tokaji|Tokay]] in Hungary.\n\nIn 2007, he was one of the few non-Hungarian citizens to be awarded Knight of Merit by the President of Hungary for his dedication for the region and wines of Tokay.\n\nIn 2008, Alta Vista was classified among the best five Argentina wineries by [[Robert Parker (wine critic)|Robert Parker]] in the 7th edition of his Wines buying guide. \n\nIn 2017, Alta Vista winery was nominated as the best new world winery in the world by ''[[Wine Enthusiast]]'' magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.almanachdegotha.org/id194.htm ] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suarez d'Aulan, Patrick de}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Czernin]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2020}}\n{{notability|biographies|date=March 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Patrick de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| birth_place   = [[Paris]], France\n| citizenship   = French and British\n| title              = [[Count]] (heir to the 11th title of [[Marquis]] of Aulan)\n| children      = [[Count]] Maximilian de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Tatiana de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Alexandra de Suarez d\u2019Aulan,<br /> [[Countess]] Anastasia de Suarez d\u2019Aulan \n| parents       = [[Countess]] and [[Marchioness]] Sonia Czernin von und zu Chudentitz ([[house of Czernin]])<br /> and [[Marquis]] Francois de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n| spouse        = [[Countess]] Kristen de Suarez d\u2019Aulan\n}}\n'''Patrick de Suarez, Count d'Aulan ''' (born 1971, [[Paris]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p9862.htm|title=Patrick de Suarez d'Aulan|website=www.thepeerage.com}}</ref>) is a French aristocrat and [[winemaker]].\n\nHe is the only male child of Francois de Suarez, 10th Marquis d'Aulan ( 1933-    ) ([[House of Suarez]] and [[House of Aulan]]) and Countess Sonia Czernin von und zu Chudentitz ( 1940\u20132007 ) ([[house of Czernin]]), being the heir of the 11th title of Marquis of Aulan, as a direct descendent of the last Kings of Bohemia. Currently, he holds the title of [[Count]] d\u2019Aulan (Earl of Aulan).{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 1999 de Suarez d'Aulan co-founded Alta Vista winery in Argentina.<ref name=sitdown>{{Cite web|url=https://www.winespectator.com/articles/a-sit-down-with-patrick-daulan-of-argentinas-alta-vista-15790|title=A Sit Down with Patrick d\u2019Aulan of Argentina\u2019s Alta Vista|website=[[Wine Spectator]]}}</ref> In 2001, he was one of the first producers in Argentina to produce single-vineyard [[Malbec]] grape wines coming from specific old vines' [[terroir]]s of Mendoza.<ref name=sitdown/>\n\nIn 1999, he founded Chateau Dereszla winery in [[Tokay]] in Hungary.\n\nIn 2007, he was one of the few non-Hungarian citizens to be awarded Knight of Merit by the President of Hungary for his dedication for the region and wines of Tokay.\n\nIn 2008, Alta Vista was classified among the best five Argentina wineries by [[Robert Parker (wine critic)|Robert Parker]] in the 7th edition of his Wines buying guide. \n\nIn 2017, Alta Vista winery was nominated as the best new world winery in the world by ''[[Wine Enthusiast]]'' magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.almanachdegotha.org/id194.htm ] {{dead link|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suarez d'Aulan, Patrick de}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:French businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Czernin]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toTokay(link changed toTokaji) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_de_Suarez_d%27Aulan"}
{"title_page": "Mirza", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Indo-Persian royal and noble ranks}}\n'''Mirza''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025c\u02d0r|z|\u0259}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u026a\u0259r|\u02c8|z|\u0251\u02d0}}; {{lang-fa|\u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com /dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref>{{efn|[[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627; [[Azeri language|Azeri]]: Mirz\u0259; [[Tajik language|Tajik]]: \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0437\u043e; [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]]: Mirzo; Russian: \u043c\u0443\u0440\u0437\u0430; [[Bashkir language|Bashkir]]: m\u00efr\u00f0a; [[Northwest Caucasian languages|Circassian]]: \u043c\u044b\u0440\u0437\u044d (common variance in [[Tatar]] nobility as [[Morza]]); [[Urdu language|Urdu]]: \u0645\u0631\u0632\u0627; [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]: \u0645\u0631\u0632\u0627 }} is a name of Persian origin. It is used as a surname or prefix to identify patriarchal lineage.\n\nIt is derived from a historical title of Persian origin (''M\u012brz\u0101''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Dictionary.com|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> denoting the rank of a [[Prince of the Blood|royal prince]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Dictionary.com|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> [[Nobleman|high nobleman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> distinguished [[Military rank|military commander]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> or a scholar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\nSpecifically, it was used as a title by and today signifies patriarchal lineage to the various [[Persian Empire]]s, the [[Shirvanshah]]s and [[Circassia]]ns of the Caucasus, and mainly the [[Mughal dynasty|Mughals / Moguls]] or [[Muslim Rajputs]] of the Indian Subcontinent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allrajputyouthwing.weebly.com/muslim-rajputs-history.html |title=History|publisher=Rana M. Ahsan Khan|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> It was also a title bestowed upon members of the highest aristocracies in [[Tatar]] states, such as the [[Khanate]]s of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]] and [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]] and the [[Nogai Horde]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''M\u012brz\u0101'' or ''Merz\u0101h'' is derived from the Persian term ''Am\u012brz\u0101deh'' which literally means ''child of the Am\u012br'' or ''child of the ruler''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref> ''Am\u012brz\u0101deh'' in turn consists of the Arabic title ''Am\u012br'' (English: ''[[Emir]]''), meaning \"commander\" and the [[Persian language|Persian]] [[suffix]] ''z\u0101deh'', meaning \"son of\" or \"lineage of\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref> Due to [[vowel harmony]] in [[Turkic languages]], the alternative pronunciation [[Morza]] (plural ''morzalar''; derived from the [[Persian language|Persian]]) is also used.\n\n==Royal Title==\nThe titles themselves were given by the Kings, [[Sultans]] and [[Emperors]] (equivalent to the western [[Fount of honour]]) to their sons and grandsons, or even distant kins. Noblemen loyal to the kings also received this [[Noble titles|Title]].\n\nThe title itself is derived from the title [[Emir]]. ''Emir'', meaning \"commander\" or \"Prince\", is derived from the Semitic [[triconsonantal|root]] ''{{transl|ar|DIN|\"Amr\"}}'', meaning \"command\". Originally it simply meant \"commander\" or \"leader\", usually in reference to a group of people. It came to be used as a title of governors or rulers, typically in smaller states, and usually renders the English word \"prince\". The word entered English in 1595, from the French ''\u00e9mir''.<ref>http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=amir&searchmode=none EtymologyOnLine</ref>\n\n==Persian Empires==\n[[File:Meeting between Babur and Sultan 'Ali Mirza near Samarqand.jpg|thumb|Meeting between [[Babur]] Mirza and Sultan [[Ali Mirza Safavi|Ali Mirza]] near [[Samarqand]]]]\n[[File:Elkas_Mirza.jpg|thumb|Alqas Mirza meeting [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]. Illustration from the ''[[S\u00fcleymanname]]''.]]\n\n===Safavid dynasty===\n\n*Padeshah [[Ali Mirza Safavi|Ali Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Alqas Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Baqer Mirza]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Shokrollah Isfahani]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Salman Jaberi]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Shah Hossein]]\n\n===Afsharid dynasty===\n\n*Prince [[Reza Qoli Mirza Afshar|Reza Qoli Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Shahrokh Afshar|Shahrokh Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Ebrahim Afshar|Ebrahim Mirza]]\n*Statesman [[Mirza Mehdi Khan Astarabadi|Mirza Mehdi Khan]]\n*Prince [[Nader Mirza Afshar|Nader Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mirza Husnain|barlash Mirza]]\n\n===Qajar dynasty===\n\n*Prince [[Iraj Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Malek Mansur Mirza Shao es-Saltaneh]]\n*Prince [[Bahram Mirza Sardar Mass'oud]]\n*Prince [[Abbas Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Abdol Majid Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Ali-Mohammad Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Bahram Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Djahangir Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Eskandar Mirza (Qajar)|Eskandar Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Hamid Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Khanlar Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Khosrow Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Muhammad Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mahmoud Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Hassan Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Hassan Mirza II]]\n*Prince [[Ahmad Shah Qajar]]\n*Prince [[Nosrat-od-Dowleh Firouz Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Firouz Mirza Nosrat-ed-Dowleh Farman Farmaian III]]\n*Prince [[Ali Mirza Qajar]]\n*Prince [[Nosrat al-Din Mirza Salar es-Saltaneh]]\n*Prince [[Abdol-samad Mirza Ezz ed-Dowleh Saloor]]\n*Prince [[Mass'oud Mirza Zell-e Soltan]]\n*Prince [[Dowlatshah|Mohammad Ali Mirza Dowlatshah]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Taqi Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Kamran Mirza Nayeb es-Saltaneh]]\n\n== Shirvanshahs ==\nThree consecutive [[Titular ruler|titular]] kings of [[Shirvan]], of the [[Shirvanshah]] Dynasty (present-day [[Azerbaijan]]), adopted the title as well following the death of [[Gurban Ali]].\n* [[Gasim Mirza]]\n* [[Kavus Mirza]]\n* [[Abu Bakr Mirza]]\n\n==Circassians==\n\n===Circassian Dynasty===\n\nThe hereditary title of Mirza was adopted by the nobility class of the [[Circassians]]. [[Idar of Kabardia]], also known as \"Mirza Haydar Temruk Bey\", was the great-grandson of Prince Inal \u2013 Sultan of Egypt the founder of the \"Temruk dynasty\" of the Kabardian princes, known in Russia as the \"Cherkassky\" a Circassian princely family.\n\nCircassian nobility with the name Mirza include:\n* [[Idar of Kabardia|Mirza Haydar Temruk Bey]] (ca. 1470 \u2013 1571)\nPrincely Issues:\n* Temruk Mirza (ca. 1501 \u2013 1571)\n* Kambulat Mirza (ca. 1510 \u2013 1589)\n* Zhelegot Mirza (ca. 1520- ?)\n\n===Russian Empire===\n\nUnder [[Catherine the Great]], empress of [[Russian Empire|Russia]], the Mirzas gained equal rights with the [[Russian nobility]] due to their extreme wealth. Abdul Mirza was given the title [[Knyaz|Prince]] [[House of Yusupov|Yusupov]], and his descendant Prince [[Felix Yusupov]] married [[Princess Irina Alexandrovna of Russia]], the only niece of Tsar [[Nicholas II]].\n\n==Mughal Empire==\n[[File:Babur_of_India.jpg|thumb|right|[[Babur]] Mirza (born Mirza Zahiruddin), first emperor of Mughal Dynasty.<ref>{{cite book |title=World Civilizations: The Global Experience, 4th Edition Outlines \u2013 Chapter 21: The Muslim Empires|publisher=Longman|year=2003}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Portrait of Akbar by Manohar.jpg|thumb|right|[[Akbar]] Mirza (born Mirza Abu'l-Fath Jalal-ud-din Muhammad), one of the most popular Mughal kings of India, known as \"Akbar the Great\".]]\n[[File:Mirzas1878.jpg|thumb|right|Mirzas of the Mughal imperial family, c. 1878.<ref>A photo from 'The People of India', published from 1868 to the early 1870s by WH Allen, for the India Office</ref>]]\nIn the [[Indian subcontinent]], the title Mirza was borne by an imperial prince. It was adopted as part of ones name, implying relationship to the Turk dynasties like the [[Mughal Emperors|Mughal Dynasty]] (the Imperial [[Timurid Dynasty|House of Timur]]).<ref>http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00urdu/hali/majalis/10glossary.html</ref> In the traditional naming sequence of the Indian royal families, the title can be placed both before the name and after it, such as Prince [[Mirza Mughal]] or Prince [[Kamran Mirza]]. Prince [[Khusrau Mirza]] was the grandson of Emperor [[Babur]] ([[Babur]] Mirza), son of Emperor [[Jahangir]] and a brother of Emperor [[Shah Jahan]]. Emperor [[Akbar Shah II]] was known as Prince [[Akbar Shah II|Mirza Akbar]] before his coronation. Emperor [[Babur]] took the imperial title of ''[[Padishah]]'' on 6 March 1508, before which he used the title ''Mirza''.<ref>pg 24. The Empire of the Great Mughals: History, Art and Culture</ref>\n\n===Mughal Dynasty of Northern India===\n\n{{further|Mughal Emperors}}\n* [[Babur|Mirza Zahirudin]] 1523\u20131530, first Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Humayun|Mirza Nasiruddin]] 1530\u20131539 & 1554\u20131555, second Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Akbar|Mirza Jalaluddin]] 1555\u20131605, third Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Jahangir|Mirza Nuruddin]] 1605\u20131627, fourth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Jahan|Mirza Khurram]] 1627\u20131658, fifth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Aurangzeb|Mirza Muhiuddin]] 1658\u20131707, sixth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Muhammad Azam Shah|Mirza Azam]] 1707, seventh Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Bahadur Shah I|Mirza Mu'Azzam]] 1707\u20131712, eighth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Jahandar Shah|Sultan Muizuddin Mirza]] 1712\u20131713, ninth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Farrukhsiyar|Mouinudd'in Muhammad Mirza]] 1712\u20131719, tenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Rafi ud-Darajat|Shamsuddin Mirza]] 1719, eleventh Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Rafi ud-Darajat|Rafiuddin Mirza (later Shah Jahan II)]] 1719, twelfth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Muhammad Shah|Sultan Nekusiyar Mirza]] 1719, thirteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Muhammad Shah|Akhtar Mirza]], fourteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Ahmad Shah Bahadur|Ahmad Shah Mirza]] 1720\u20131748, fifteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Alamgir II|Aziz 'ud-Din Beg Mirza]] 1754\u20131759, sixteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Alam II|Jalal 'ud-Din Mirza]] 1759\u20131760, seventeenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Jahan III|Muhi-ul-millat Mirza]] 1788\u20131806, eighteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Akbar Shah II|Mirza Akbar]] 1806\u20131837, nineteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Bahadur Shah II|Sirajuddin Mirza]] 1837\u20131857, Mughal Emperor.\n* Mirza Abdullah, son of [[Bahadur Shah II]] 1850\u20131897, Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Mirza Aziz Koka]] (1542\u20131624), foster-brother of Akbar, son of [[Ataga Khan]]\n\n===Royal Family of Bengal===\n\nImperial Families of Central India and Bengal\nThe archaic Bengali form of ''Mirza'' was ''Mridha'' in [[Bengal]] and [[Bihar]].<ref>The [[Khan Mohammad Mridha Mosque]] is named for a man known in Mughal records as Khan ''Muhammad Mirza''; see https://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=4450 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101117111751/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=4450 |date=17 November 2010 }} [[Mughal Emperors|Mughal dynasty]] (the Imperial [[Timurid Dynasty|House of Timur]] \"Sarai Mulk Khanam Qutubuddunniya wa Deen Amir Qutubuddin Taimur Baig Sahib-e-kiran\").</ref>\n\n{{further|Nawabs of Bengal}}\n* [[Shuja-ud-Din Muhammad Khan|Mirza Shuja ud-din Muhammad Khan]], second Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Sarfaraz Khan|Mirza Asadullah]], third Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Alivardi Khan|Mirza Muhammad Ali]], fourth Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Siraj ud-Daulah|Mirza Mohammad Siraj]], fifth Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Hassan Ali Mirza Khan Bahadur|Mirza Hassan Ali Khan Bahadur]], 18th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Wasif Ali Mirza Khan|Mirza Wasif Ali Khan]], 19th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Waris Ali Mirza Khan Bahadur|Mirza Waris Ali Khan]], 20th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n\n===Royal Family of Awadh===\n\n{{further|Nawab of Awadh}}\n* [[Safdarjung|Mirza Muhammad Muqim Ali Khan]], second Nawab Subahdar of Awadh (Oudh)\n* [[Asaf-Ud-Dowlah|Mirza Amani Asif-ud-Dawlah]], fourth Nawab Subahdar of Awadh\n* [[Wazir Ali Khan|Mirza Asif Jah Wazir Ali Khan]], fifth Nawab Subahdar of Awadh\n* [[Wajid Ali Shah|Mirza Wajid Ali Shah]], eleventh Nawab Subahdar (fifth King) of Awadh\n\n==Rajput Dynasty==\n\n===Rajputs of Northern India===\n\nOriginally being adversaries and opponents to the Mughal Emperors of Northern India, the title ''Mirza'' was also adopted by the [[Muslim Rajput]]s of Northern India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allrajputyouthwing.weebly.com/muslim-rajputs-history.html |title=History: Muslim Rajputs|publisher=Rana M. Ahsan Khan|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> The Rajput imperial families were descendants of ancient [[Indo-Aryan people|Indo-Aryan]] warriors who strategically formed blood alliances with [[Mughal tribe|Mughal]] aristocracy. The Rajputs were rulers of [[princely states]] comprising vast territories of Northern India, including the [[Punjab Region]], [[Kashmir]] and [[Rajasthan]]. Inter-marriage between Mughal aristocracy and Rajput aristocracy became very common and various factions of Rajput kingdoms embraced the [[Islam]]ic faith, giving rise to the term \"Muslim Rajputs\".<ref>''Lord Lawrence and the Reconstruction of India Under The Crown'' by Sir Charles Aitcheson, K.C.S.I., M.A., LL.D., [[Rulers of India series]], Clarendon Press 1897, V p117</ref> Rajput rulers were also granted the title ''Mirza'' on account of being high-ranked commanders in the Mughal military.<ref>[http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00702051%26ct%3D237%26rqs%3D302%26rqs%3D309%26rqs%3D310 30. Ra\u00b4jah Ma\u00b4n Singh, son of Bhagw\u00e1n D\u00e1s \u2013 Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007092053/http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00702051%26ct%3D237%26rqs%3D302%26rqs%3D309%26rqs%3D310 |date=7 October 2016 }} [[Ain-i-Akbari]], Vol. I.</ref> The meaning of ''Mirza'' (Persian origin)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=n.d.}}</ref> is identical to the meaning of ''Rajput'' (Sanskrit Origin).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Rajput|title=Rajput Definition|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable Mirzas==\n===Sport===\n* [[Sania Mirza]], Indian tennis player, former WTA number 1\n* [[Fadi Merza]], Syrian-Austrian middleweight kickboxer, former world champion kickboxing and Muay Thai\n* [[Mirza Ali Baig]], Pakistani [[mountaineer]]\n* [[Mirza Ba\u0161i\u0107]], Bosnian tennis player, winner 2018 Sofia Open\n* [[Mirza Begi\u0107]], Slovenian Olympic basketball player\n* [[Mirza Delibasic|Mirza Deliba\u0161i\u0107]], Bosnian basketball player\n* [[Mirza Teletovi\u0107]], Bosnian basketball player\n* [[Rasul Mirzaev]], Russian MMA fighter\n\n===Academics and literature===\n* [[Heidi Safia Mirza]] (born 1958), British academic\n* [[Iraj Mirza]], Persian folk poet, also known as Jalaal-al-mamalek.\n* [[Mirza Abu Taleb Khan]], tax-collector and administrator from northern India, writer of an early travel guide to Europe.\n* [[Mirza Athar Baig]] is a Pakistani novelist, playwright and short story writer.\n* [[G\u02bbafur G\u02bbulom|Mirza G\u02bbafur G\u02bbulom]], Uzbek poet, writer, and literary translator, considered one of the most influential Uzbek writers of the 20th century. \n* [[Mirza Ghalib]] (born Mirza Asadullah Baig Khan), a [[Urdu]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] poet from South Asia who adorned the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] court.\n* [[Mirza Kalich Beg]], Sindhi writer.\n* [[Mirza Sahiba|Mirza Khan]] of \"Mirza & Sahiba\", a tragic romance story, based on true events, which is enshrined in [[Punjabi culture|Punjabi]] literature and commonly told in the [[Punjab region]]. Mirza of \"Mirza & Sahiba\" was of Kharal [[Muslim Rajput]] / [[Muslim Jat]] tribe of Puar [[Rajput]] descent. \n* [[Muhammad Munawwar Mirza]], a prominent scholar, historian, writer and intellectual from Pakistan.\n* Nawab Mirza Khan \"[[Daagh]]\", Urdu poet.\n*Mirza Beigh Family from Jammu & Kashmir's [[Srinagar]] district have immensely worked and contributed for [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Literature under the genre of elegy commonly called \"Kashmiri [[noha]]\". Some of noted family members include Mirza Abdul Ghani Beigh, Mirza Manzoor Hussain Beigh and Mirza Sharafat Hussain Beigh.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Shi'as of Jammu & Kashmir|last=Justice|first=Hakim Imtiyaz|last2=Hussain|publisher=Srinagar Publishing House|year=2017|isbn=|location=Srinagar Jammu & Kashmir|pages=508\u2013509}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n* [[Aziz Mirza]] (born 1947), Indian film director, producer and writer.\n* [[Dia Mirza]], Indian actress and former \"Miss Asia Pacific\" titleholder.\n* [[Haji Mastan|Mastan Haider Mirza]], Indian Mafia boss, mobster and filmmaker; popularly known as the first \"celebrity gangster\" of Bombay.\n* [[Mirza Babayev]], Azerbaijani movie actor and singer. Honored Artist of the Azerbaijan SSR and People's Artist of Azerbaijan.\n*[[Nadeem Baig (actor)|Mirza Nadeem Baig]] Mirza Nazeer Baig Mughal better known by his stage name Nadeem Baig, a Pakistani actor, singer and producer.\n* [[Mohib Mirza]] is a Pakistani actor and television host.\n* [[Saeed Akhtar Mirza|Saeed Mirza]], Indian film director and screenwriter, considered one of the most influential parallel cinema movie makers in India.\n\n===Arts===\n* [[Bashir Mirza]] also known as BM, a Pakistani painter.\n* [[Haroon Mirza]], Anglo-Pakistani artist born in London.\n* [[Mirza Kadym Irevani]], Azerbaijani artist.\n* [[Shazia Mirza]], English comedian.\n\n===Government===\n* [[Mirza Fakhrul Islam Alamgir]],  Bangladeshi politician, the incumbent secretary general of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) since 2016\n* [[Mirza Abbas]],  [[Bangladesh Nationalist Party]] politician. He was the Mayor of Dhaka City Corporation from 1991 to 1993\n* [[Fahmida Mirza]], first female Speaker of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] \n*[[Hasnain Mirza]], lawyer, [[barrister]] and Member of Parliament who was Member of Provincial Assembly(MPA) \n* [[Iskandar Ali Mirza]], the first [[President of Pakistan|President]] and 4th [[Governor-General of Pakistan|Governor General]] of the [[Islamic Republic of Pakistan]] in 1956 \n*[[Mirza Ali Asghar Khan Amin al-Soltan]], the last prime minister of [[Qajar dynasty|Iran]]<nowiki/>under [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] \n* [[Mirza Ismail]], Prime Minister, [[Jaipur]] (Diwan of Jaipur) (1942\u20131946) \n*[[Mirza Kuchik Khan]], early 20th-century revolutionary, [[Gilan Province|Gilani]] [[Nationalism|Nationalist]] and the president of the [[Persian Socialist Soviet Republic|Republic Of Gilan]] \n* [[Mirza Muzaffar Ahmad]], a [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Federal Finance Minister]] and [[Finance Secretary of Pakistan|Finance Secretary]], Chairman of [[Planning Commission of Pakistan]] Executive director of the [[World bank]] \n*[[Mirza Nasrullah Khan]], the first Iranian Prime Minister\n*[[Munira Mirza]], Deputy Mayor of London \n*[[Zulfiqar Mirza]], Pakistani politician affiliated with the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP)\n*[[Mirza Azaz Ahammed Tushar]], Ex Student leader of University of Rajshahi, Bangladesh.\n\n=== Judges and advocates ===\n* ''Jerome Mirza'' (1937-2007), was a prominent American lawyer, [[barrister]], published author and philanthropist. A native of [[Chicago]], he was a prominent member of the [[Illinois]] legal community from the early 1960s until his passing. He ran a multi-million dollar legal practice, was the former president of the Illinois State Bar Association and Illinois Trial Lawyers Association, founded the Jerome Mirza College of Advocacy at [[Illinois Wesleyan University]] and the [[University of Illinois]] and published numerous legal textbooks, including \"Winning Litigation the Mirza Way\". He is survived by the Jerome Mirza Foundation and Mirza and Associates, which continues to operate as a prominent boutique law firm in Illinois. \n* [[Mirza Aziz Akbar Baig]], Former Vice Chairman of [[Pakistan Bar Council]].\n* [[Zafar Hussain Mirza]], Pakistani judge and the father of former Home Minister of Sindh [[Zulfiqar Mirza]].\n\n=== Journalist ===\n* [[Janbaz Mirza]] was a writer, poet, and journalist from [[Pakistan]].\n* [[Tahir Mirza]] was a senior Pakistani journalist and former editor of [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]], [[Pakistan]]'s oldest and most widely circulated [[English-language]] newspaper.\n\n===Military===\n*[[4th Horse (Hodson's Horse)|Mirza Ahmed Bey]], one of the original [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] soldiers of the famed \"Hodson's Horse\" regiment of the British Indian Army, pictured in the historical 1858 photograph.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP-->{{Circular reference|date=November 2017}} He was a descendant of Mirza Hakim Bey, after whom the Indian village Hakimpur, Gurdaspur District is named.\n* [[Mirza Aslam Baig]] a Former Chief of Army Staff of Pakistan.\n* [[Mirza Ghulam Murtaza]] was the chieftain of [[Qadian]] and a commander withn the [[Sikh Army]].\n* [[Mirza Kuchak Khan]] was a Persian revolutionary who led the Jungle Movement in the northern jungles of [[Gilan Province]].\n\n===Nobility===\n* [[Khan Mohammad Mridha Mosque|Khan Muhammad Mirza]], Architect during the Mughal Era.\n* [[Mirza Ali Behrouze Ispahani]],  Bangladeshi businessman from the [[Ispahani family]] and the chairman of [[M. M. Ispahani Limited]].\n* [[Mirza Hadi Baig]], Mughal nobleman from [[Samarkand]] who was granted 80 villages by [[Babur]].\n* [[Mirza Najaf Khan]], Indian Courtier and Commander in Chief of the Mughal Imperial Army.\n* [[Sikandar Mirza]], Armenian courtier within [[Akbar's Mughal Empire]]\n\n== Movies ==\n* ''[[Mirza \u2013 The Untold Story]]'' \u2013 Punjabi language Movie from India\n* [[Mirzya (film)|''Mirzya'' (film)]] \u2013 Hindi language Movie from India \n* ''[[Mirza Juuliet]]'' \u2013 Hindi language Movie from India\n\n== See also ==\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n* [[Rana (title)]]\n*[[Baig]], [[Bey]]\n*[[Beg Khan]]\n*[[Emir]]\n*[[Khanzada]]\n*[[Begzada]] {{nb10}}\n*[[Morza]]\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Mughal (tribe)]]\n*[[Muslim Rajput]]\n*[[Nawab]]\n*[[Shah#Shahzada|Shahzada]]\n*[[Sultanzada]]\n*[[Mirza Ghassemi]]\n*[[Sayyid]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*''Life of a Mirza'' Chapter 7 (pg 225\u2013227) The Empire of the Great Mughals: History, Art and Culture (2004) by ''Annemarie Schimmel'' {{ISBN|1-86189-185-7}}\n*''Mirzah'' in The Wordsworth Dictionary of Phrase and Fable By Ebenezer Cobham Brewer: The quintessential guide to myth, folklore, legend, legend and literature. {{ISBN|1-84022-310-3}}\n*''MI\u2019RZA'' Chambers's Encyclopaedia: A Dictionary of Universal Knowledge For the People. {{ISBN|1-149-98693-X}}\n*A. Jaimoukha  ''The Circassians'': A Handbook ''Routledge, Palgrave, 2001'', pp 157\u201360) {{ISBN|0-312-23994-7}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n;Specific \n{{reflist}}\n;Sources\n*''Brewer's Dictionary of Phrases and Fable'', 16th edition Revised by Adrian Room, 1999\n*[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Religious_Organizations.html#Caliphate WorldStatesmen]\n*[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=amir&searchmode=none Etymology Online]\n\n[[Category:Noble titles]]\n[[Category:Surnames]]\n[[Category:Court titles]]\n[[Category:Royal titles]]\n[[Category:Titles in Iran]]\n[[Category:Titles in Azerbaijan]]\n[[Category:Titles in Russia]]\n[[Category:Titles in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:Turkish titles]]\n[[Category:Turkic culture]]\n[[Category:Titles in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Persian words and phrases]]\n[[Category:Pakistani families]]\n[[Category:Muslim families]]\n[[Category:Mughal nobility]]\n[[Category:Ottoman titles]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Indo-Persian royal and noble ranks}}\n'''Mirza''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u025c\u02d0r|z|\u0259}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u026a\u0259r|\u02c8|z|\u0251\u02d0}}; {{lang-fa|\u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com /dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref>{{efn|[[Persian language|Persian]]: \u0645\u06cc\u0631\u0632\u0627; [[Azeri language|Azeri]]: Mirz\u0259; [[Tajik language|Tajik]]: \u041c\u0438\u0440\u0437\u043e; [[Uzbek language|Uzbek]]: Mirzo; Russian: \u043c\u0443\u0440\u0437\u0430; [[Bashkir language|Bashkir]]: m\u00efr\u00f0a; [[Northwest Caucasian languages|Circassian]]: \u043c\u044b\u0440\u0437\u044d (common variance in [[Tatar]] nobility as [[Morza]]); [[Urdu language|Urdu]]: \u0645\u0631\u0632\u0627; [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]: \u0645\u0631\u0632\u0627 }} is a name of Persian origin. It is used as a surname or prefix to identify patriarchal lineage.\n\nIt is derived from a historical title of Persian origin (''M\u012brz\u0101''),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Dictionary.com|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> denoting the rank of a [[Prince of the Blood|royal prince]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dictionary.com/browse/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Dictionary.com|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> [[Nobleman|high nobleman]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> distinguished [[Military rank|military commander]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/mirza|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Merriam-Webster|accessdate=14 January 2018|date=n.d.}}</ref> or a scholar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\nSpecifically, it was used as a title by and today signifies patriarchal lineage to the various [[Persian Empire]]s, the [[Shirvanshah]]s and [[Circassia]]ns of the Caucasus, and mainly the [[Mughal dynasty|Mughals / Moguls]] or [[Muslim Rajputs]] of the Indian Subcontinent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allrajputyouthwing.weebly.com/muslim-rajputs-history.html |title=History|publisher=Rana M. Ahsan Khan|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> It was also a title bestowed upon members of the highest aristocracies in [[Tatar]] states, such as the [[Khanate]]s of [[Khanate of Kazan|Kazan]] and [[Astrakhan Khanate|Astrakhan]] and the [[Nogai Horde]].\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word ''M\u012brz\u0101'' or ''Merz\u0101h'' is derived from the Persian term ''Am\u012brz\u0101deh'' which literally means ''child of the Am\u012br'' or ''child of the ruler''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref> ''Am\u012brz\u0101deh'' in turn consists of the Arabic title ''Am\u012br'' (English: ''[[Emir]]''), meaning \"commander\" and the [[Persian language|Persian]] [[suffix]] ''z\u0101deh'', meaning \"son of\" or \"lineage of\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=15 October 2014|date=n.d.}}</ref> Due to [[vowel harmony]] in [[Turkic languages]], the alternative pronunciation [[Morza]] (plural ''morzalar''; derived from the [[Persian language|Persian]]) is also used.\n\n==Royal Title==\nThe titles themselves were given by the Kings, [[Sultans]] and [[Emperors]] (equivalent to the western [[Fount of honour]]) to their sons and grandsons, or even distant kins. Noblemen loyal to the kings also received this [[Noble titles|Title]].\n\nThe title itself is derived from the title [[Emir]]. ''Emir'', meaning \"commander\" or \"Prince\", is derived from the Semitic [[triconsonantal|root]] ''{{transl|ar|DIN|\"Amr\"}}'', meaning \"command\". Originally it simply meant \"commander\" or \"leader\", usually in reference to a group of people. It came to be used as a title of governors or rulers, typically in smaller states, and usually renders the English word \"prince\". The word entered English in 1595, from the French ''\u00e9mir''.<ref>http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=amir&searchmode=none EtymologyOnLine</ref>\n\n==Persian Empires==\n[[File:Meeting between Babur and Sultan 'Ali Mirza near Samarqand.jpg|thumb|Meeting between [[Babur]] Mirza and Sultan [[Ali Mirza Safavi|Ali Mirza]] near [[Samarqand]]]]\n[[File:Elkas_Mirza.jpg|thumb|Alqas Mirza meeting [[Suleiman the Magnificent]]. Illustration from the ''[[S\u00fcleymanname]]''.]]\n\n===Safavid dynasty===\n\n*Padeshah [[Ali Mirza Safavi|Ali Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Alqas Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Baqer Mirza]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Shokrollah Isfahani]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Salman Jaberi]]\n*Vizier [[Mirza Shah Hossein]]\n\n===Afsharid dynasty===\n\n*Prince [[Reza Qoli Mirza Afshar|Reza Qoli Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Shahrokh Afshar|Shahrokh Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Ebrahim Afshar|Ebrahim Mirza]]\n*Statesman [[Mirza Mehdi Khan Astarabadi|Mirza Mehdi Khan]]\n*Prince [[Nader Mirza Afshar|Nader Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mirza Husnain|barlash Mirza]]\n\n===Qajar dynasty===\n\n*Prince [[Iraj Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Malek Mansur Mirza Shao es-Saltaneh]]\n*Prince [[Bahram Mirza Sardar Mass'oud]]\n*Prince [[Abbas Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Abdol Majid Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Ali-Mohammad Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Bahram Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Djahangir Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Eskandar Mirza (Qajar)|Eskandar Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Hamid Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Khanlar Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Khosrow Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Muhammad Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mahmoud Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Hassan Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Hassan Mirza II]]\n*Prince [[Ahmad Shah Qajar]]\n*Prince [[Nosrat-od-Dowleh Firouz Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Firouz Mirza Nosrat-ed-Dowleh Farman Farmaian III]]\n*Prince [[Ali Mirza Qajar]]\n*Prince [[Nosrat al-Din Mirza Salar es-Saltaneh]]\n*Prince [[Abdol-samad Mirza Ezz ed-Dowleh Saloor]]\n*Prince [[Mass'oud Mirza Zell-e Soltan]]\n*Prince [[Dowlatshah|Mohammad Ali Mirza Dowlatshah]]\n*Prince [[Mohammad Taqi Mirza]]\n*Prince [[Kamran Mirza Nayeb es-Saltaneh]]\n\n== Shirvanshahs ==\nThree consecutive [[Titular ruler|titular]] kings of [[Shirvan]], of the [[Shirvanshah]] Dynasty (present-day [[Azerbaijan]]), adopted the title as well following the death of [[Gurban Ali]].\n* [[Gasim Mirza]]\n* [[Kavus Mirza]]\n* [[Abu Bakr Mirza]]\n\n==Circassians==\n\n===Circassian Dynasty===\n\nThe hereditary title of Mirza was adopted by the nobility class of the [[Circassians]]. [[Idar of Kabardia]], also known as \"Mirza Haydar Temruk Bey\", was the great-grandson of Prince Inal \u2013 Sultan of Egypt the founder of the \"Temruk dynasty\" of the Kabardian princes, known in Russia as the \"Cherkassky\" a Circassian princely family.\n\nCircassian nobility with the name Mirza include:\n* [[Idar of Kabardia|Mirza Haydar Temruk Bey]] (ca. 1470 \u2013 1571)\nPrincely Issues:\n* Temruk Mirza (ca. 1501 \u2013 1571)\n* Kambulat Mirza (ca. 1510 \u2013 1589)\n* Zhelegot Mirza (ca. 1520- ?)\n\n===Russian Empire===\n\nUnder [[Catherine the Great]], empress of [[Russian Empire|Russia]], the Mirzas gained equal rights with the [[Russian nobility]] due to their extreme wealth. Abdul Mirza was given the title [[Knyaz|Prince]] [[House of Yusupov|Yusupov]], and his descendant Prince [[Felix Yusupov]] married [[Princess Irina Alexandrovna of Russia]], the only niece of Tsar [[Nicholas II]].\n\n==Mughal Empire==\n[[File:Babur_of_India.jpg|thumb|right|[[Babur]] Mirza (born Mirza Zahiruddin), first emperor of Mughal Dynasty.<ref>{{cite book |title=World Civilizations: The Global Experience, 4th Edition Outlines \u2013 Chapter 21: The Muslim Empires|publisher=Longman|year=2003}}</ref>]]\n[[File:Portrait of Akbar by Manohar.jpg|thumb|right|[[Akbar]] Mirza (born Mirza Abu'l-Fath Jalal-ud-din Muhammad), one of the most popular Mughal kings of India, known as \"Akbar the Great\".]]\n[[File:Mirzas1878.jpg|thumb|right|Mirzas of the Mughal imperial family, c. 1878.<ref>A photo from 'The People of India', published from 1868 to the early 1870s by WH Allen, for the India Office</ref>]]\nIn the [[Indian subcontinent]], the title Mirza was borne by an imperial prince. It was adopted as part of ones name, implying relationship to the Turk dynasties like the [[Mughal Emperors|Mughal Dynasty]] (the Imperial [[Timurid Dynasty|House of Timur]]).<ref>http://www.columbia.edu/itc/mealac/pritchett/00urdu/hali/majalis/10glossary.html</ref> In the traditional naming sequence of the Indian royal families, the title can be placed both before the name and after it, such as Prince [[Mirza Mughal]] or Prince [[Kamran Mirza]]. Prince [[Khusrau Mirza]] was the grandson of Emperor [[Babur]] ([[Babur]] Mirza), son of Emperor [[Jahangir]] and a brother of Emperor [[Shah Jahan]]. Emperor [[Akbar Shah II]] was known as Prince [[Akbar Shah II|Mirza Akbar]] before his coronation. Emperor [[Babur]] took the imperial title of ''[[Padishah]]'' on 6 March 1508, before which he used the title ''Mirza''.<ref>pg 24. The Empire of the Great Mughals: History, Art and Culture</ref>\n\n===Mughal Dynasty of Northern India===\n\n{{further|Mughal Emperors}}\n* [[Babur|Mirza Zahirudin]] 1523\u20131530, first Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Humayun|Mirza Nasiruddin]] 1530\u20131539 & 1554\u20131555, second Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Akbar|Mirza Jalaluddin]] 1555\u20131605, third Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Jahangir|Mirza Nuruddin]] 1605\u20131627, fourth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Jahan|Mirza Khurram]] 1627\u20131658, fifth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Aurangzeb|Mirza Muhiuddin]] 1658\u20131707, sixth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Muhammad Azam Shah|Mirza Azam]] 1707, seventh Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Bahadur Shah I|Mirza Mu'Azzam]] 1707\u20131712, eighth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Jahandar Shah|Sultan Muizuddin Mirza]] 1712\u20131713, ninth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Farrukhsiyar|Mouinudd'in Muhammad Mirza]] 1712\u20131719, tenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Rafi ud-Darajat|Shamsuddin Mirza]] 1719, eleventh Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Rafi ud-Darajat|Rafiuddin Mirza (later Shah Jahan II)]] 1719, twelfth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Muhammad Shah|Sultan Nekusiyar Mirza]] 1719, thirteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Sultan]] [[Muhammad Shah|Akhtar Mirza]], fourteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Ahmad Shah Bahadur|Ahmad Shah Mirza]] 1720\u20131748, fifteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Alamgir II|Aziz 'ud-Din Beg Mirza]] 1754\u20131759, sixteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Alam II|Jalal 'ud-Din Mirza]] 1759\u20131760, seventeenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Shah Jahan III|Muhi-ul-millat Mirza]] 1788\u20131806, eighteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Akbar Shah II|Mirza Akbar]] 1806\u20131837, nineteenth Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Bahadur Shah II|Sirajuddin Mirza]] 1837\u20131857, Mughal Emperor.\n* Mirza Abdullah, son of [[Bahadur Shah II]] 1850\u20131897, Mughal Emperor.\n* [[Mirza Aziz Koka]] (1542\u20131624), foster-brother of Akbar, son of [[Ataga Khan]]\n\n===Royal Family of Bengal===\n\nImperial Families of Central India and Bengal\nThe archaic Bengali form of ''Mirza'' was ''Mridha'' in [[Bengal]] and [[Bihar]].<ref>The [[Khan Mohammad Mridha Mosque]] is named for a man known in Mughal records as Khan ''Muhammad Mirza''; see https://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=4450 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101117111751/http://archnet.org/library/sites/one-site.jsp?site_id=4450 |date=17 November 2010 }} [[Mughal Emperors|Mughal dynasty]] (the Imperial [[Timurid Dynasty|House of Timur]] \"Sarai Mulk Khanam Qutubuddunniya wa Deen Amir Qutubuddin Taimur Baig Sahib-e-kiran\").</ref>\n\n{{further|Nawabs of Bengal}}\n* [[Shuja-ud-Din Muhammad Khan|Mirza Shuja ud-din Muhammad Khan]], second Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Sarfaraz Khan|Mirza Asadullah]], third Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Alivardi Khan|Mirza Muhammad Ali]], fourth Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Siraj ud-Daulah|Mirza Mohammad Siraj]], fifth Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Hassan Ali Mirza Khan Bahadur|Mirza Hassan Ali Khan Bahadur]], 18th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Wasif Ali Mirza Khan|Mirza Wasif Ali Khan]], 19th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n* [[Nawab Sayyid Waris Ali Mirza Khan Bahadur|Mirza Waris Ali Khan]], 20th Nawab of Bengal, Bihar and Orissa.\n\n===Royal Family of Awadh===\n\n{{further|Nawab of Awadh}}\n* [[Safdarjung|Mirza Muhammad Muqim Ali Khan]], second Nawab Subahdar of Awadh (Oudh)\n* [[Asaf-Ud-Dowlah|Mirza Amani Asif-ud-Dawlah]], fourth Nawab Subahdar of Awadh\n* [[Wazir Ali Khan|Mirza Asif Jah Wazir Ali Khan]], fifth Nawab Subahdar of Awadh\n* [[Wajid Ali Shah|Mirza Wajid Ali Shah]], eleventh Nawab Subahdar (fifth King) of Awadh\n\n==Rajput Dynasty==\n\n===Rajputs of Northern India===\n\nOriginally being adversaries and opponents to the Mughal Emperors of Northern India, the title ''Mirza'' was also adopted by the [[Muslim Rajput]]s of Northern India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allrajputyouthwing.weebly.com/muslim-rajputs-history.html |title=History: Muslim Rajputs|publisher=Rana M. Ahsan Khan|accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> The Rajput imperial families were descendants of ancient [[Indo-Aryan people|Indo-Aryan]] warriors who strategically formed blood alliances with [[Mughal tribe|Mughal]] aristocracy. The Rajputs were rulers of [[princely states]] comprising vast territories of Northern India, including the [[Punjab Region]], [[Kashmir]] and [[Rajasthan]]. Inter-marriage between Mughal aristocracy and Rajput aristocracy became very common and various factions of Rajput kingdoms embraced the [[Islam]]ic faith, giving rise to the term \"Muslim Rajputs\".<ref>''Lord Lawrence and the Reconstruction of India Under The Crown'' by Sir Charles Aitcheson, K.C.S.I., M.A., LL.D., [[Rulers of India series]], Clarendon Press 1897, V p117</ref> Rajput rulers were also granted the title ''Mirza'' on account of being high-ranked commanders in the Mughal military.<ref>[http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00702051%26ct%3D237%26rqs%3D302%26rqs%3D309%26rqs%3D310 30. Ra\u00b4jah Ma\u00b4n Singh, son of Bhagw\u00e1n D\u00e1s \u2013 Biography] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007092053/http://persian.packhum.org/persian/main?url=pf%3Ffile%3D00702051%26ct%3D237%26rqs%3D302%26rqs%3D309%26rqs%3D310 |date=7 October 2016 }} [[Ain-i-Akbari]], Vol. I.</ref> The meaning of ''Mirza'' (Persian origin)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/mirza?showCookiePolicy=true|title=Mirza Definition|publisher=Collins Dictionary|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=n.d.}}</ref> is identical to the meaning of ''Rajput'' (Sanskrit Origin).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Rajput|title=Rajput Definition|work=Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=n.d.}}</ref>\n\n==Other notable Mirzas==\n===Sport===\n* [[Sania Mirza]], Indian tennis player, former WTA number 1\n* [[Fadi Merza]], Syrian-Austrian middleweight kickboxer, former world champion kickboxing and Muay Thai\n* [[Mirza Ali Baig]], Pakistani [[mountaineer]]\n* [[Mirza Ba\u0161i\u0107]], Bosnian tennis player, winner 2018 Sofia Open\n* [[Mirza Begi\u0107]], Slovenian Olympic basketball player\n* [[Mirza Delibasic|Mirza Deliba\u0161i\u0107]], Bosnian basketball player\n* [[Mirza Teletovi\u0107]], Bosnian basketball player\n* [[Rasul Mirzaev]], Russian MMA fighter\n\n===Academics and literature===\n* [[Heidi Safia Mirza]] (born 1958), British academic\n* [[Iraj Mirza]], Persian folk poet, also known as Jalaal-al-mamalek.\n* [[Mirza Abu Taleb Khan]], tax-collector and administrator from northern India, writer of an early travel guide to Europe.\n* [[Mirza Athar Baig]] is a Pakistani novelist, playwright and short story writer.\n* [[G\u02bbafur G\u02bbulom|Mirza G\u02bbafur G\u02bbulom]], Uzbek poet, writer, and literary translator, considered one of the most influential Uzbek writers of the 20th century. \n* [[Mirza Ghalib]] (born Mirza Asadullah Baig Khan), a [[Urdu]] and [[Persian people|Persian]] poet from South Asia who adorned the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] court.\n* [[Mirza Kalich Beg]], Sindhi writer.\n* [[Mirza Sahiba|Mirza Khan]] of \"Mirza & Sahiba\", a tragic romance story, based on true events, which is enshrined in [[Punjabi culture|Punjabi]] literature and commonly told in the [[Punjab region]]. Mirza of \"Mirza & Sahiba\" was of Kharal [[Muslim Rajput]] / [[Muslim Jat]] tribe of Puar [[Rajput]] descent. \n* [[Muhammad Munawwar Mirza]], a prominent scholar, historian, writer and intellectual from Pakistan.\n* Nawab Mirza Khan \"[[Daagh]]\", Urdu poet.\n*Mirza Beigh Family from Jammu & Kashmir's [[Srinagar]] district have immensely worked and contributed for [[Shia Islam|Shia]] Literature under the genre of elegy commonly called \"Kashmiri [[noha]]\". Some of noted family members include Mirza Abdul Ghani Beigh, Mirza Manzoor Hussain Beigh and Mirza Sharafat Hussain Beigh.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Shi'as of Jammu & Kashmir|last=Justice|first=Hakim Imtiyaz|last2=Hussain|publisher=Srinagar Publishing House|year=2017|isbn=|location=Srinagar Jammu & Kashmir|pages=508\u2013509}}</ref>\n\n=== Entertainment ===\n* [[Aziz Mirza]] (born 1947), Indian film director, producer and writer.\n* [[Dia Mirza]], Indian actress and former \"Miss Asia Pacific\" titleholder.\n* [[Haji Mastan|Mastan Haider Mirza]], Indian Mafia boss, mobster and filmmaker; popularly known as the first \"celebrity gangster\" of Bombay.\n* [[Mirza Babayev]], Azerbaijani movie actor and singer. Honored Artist of the Azerbaijan SSR and People's Artist of Azerbaijan.\n*[[Nadeem Baig (actor)|Mirza Nadeem Baig]] Mirza Nazeer Baig Mughal better known by his stage name Nadeem Baig, a Pakistani actor, singer and producer.\n* [[Mohib Mirza]] is a Pakistani actor and television host.\n* [[Saeed Akhtar Mirza|Saeed Mirza]], Indian film director and screenwriter, considered one of the most influential parallel cinema movie makers in India.\n\n===Arts===\n* [[Bashir Mirza]] also known as BM, a Pakistani painter.\n* [[Haroon Mirza]], Anglo-Pakistani artist born in London.\n* [[Mirza Kadym Irevani]], Azerbaijani artist.\n* [[Shazia Mirza]], English comedian.\n\n===Government===\n* [[Mirza Fakhrul Islam Alamgir]],  Bangladeshi politician, the incumbent secretary general of the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) since 2016\n* [[Mirza Abbas]],  [[Bangladesh Nationalist Party]] politician. He was the Mayor of Dhaka City Corporation from 1991 to 1993\n* [[Fahmida Mirza]], first female Speaker of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] \n*[[Hasnain Mirza]], lawyer, [[barrister]] and Member of Parliament who was Member of Provincial Assembly(MPA) \n* [[Iskandar Ali Mirza]], the first [[President of Pakistan|President]] and 4th [[Governor-General of Pakistan|Governor General]] of the [[Islamic Republic of Pakistan]] in 1956 \n*[[Mirza Ali Asghar Khan Amin al-Soltan]], the last prime minister of [[Qajar dynasty|Iran]]<nowiki/>under [[Naser al-Din Shah Qajar]] \n* [[Mirza Ismail]], Prime Minister, [[Jaipur]] (Diwan of Jaipur) (1942\u20131946) \n*[[Mirza Kuchik Khan]], early 20th-century revolutionary, [[Gilan Province|Gilani]] [[Nationalism|Nationalist]] and the president of the [[Persian Socialist Soviet Republic|Republic Of Gilan]] \n* [[Mirza Muzaffar Ahmad]], a [[Finance Minister of Pakistan|Federal Finance Minister]] and [[Finance Secretary of Pakistan|Finance Secretary]], Chairman of [[Planning Commission of Pakistan]] Executive director of the [[World bank]] \n*[[Mirza Nasrullah Khan]], the first Iranian Prime Minister\n*[[Munira Mirza]], Deputy Mayor of London \n*[[Zulfiqar Mirza]], Pakistani politician affiliated with the [[Pakistan Peoples Party]] (PPP)\n\n=== Judges and advocates ===\n* ''Jerome Mirza'' (1937-2007), was a prominent American lawyer, [[barrister]], published author and philanthropist. A native of [[Chicago]], he was a prominent member of the [[Illinois]] legal community from the early 1960s until his passing. He ran a multi-million dollar legal practice, was the former president of the Illinois State Bar Association and Illinois Trial Lawyers Association, founded the Jerome Mirza College of Advocacy at [[Illinois Wesleyan University]] and the [[University of Illinois]] and published numerous legal textbooks, including \"Winning Litigation the Mirza Way\". He is survived by the Jerome Mirza Foundation and Mirza and Associates, which continues to operate as a prominent boutique law firm in Illinois. \n* [[Mirza Aziz Akbar Baig]], Former Vice Chairman of [[Pakistan Bar Council]].\n* [[Zafar Hussain Mirza]], Pakistani judge and the father of former Home Minister of Sindh [[Zulfiqar Mirza]].\n\n=== Journalist ===\n* [[Janbaz Mirza]] was a writer, poet, and journalist from [[Pakistan]].\n* [[Tahir Mirza]] was a senior Pakistani journalist and former editor of [[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]], [[Pakistan]]'s oldest and most widely circulated [[English-language]] newspaper.\n\n===Military===\n*[[4th Horse (Hodson's Horse)|Mirza Ahmed Bey]], one of the original [[Punjabis|Punjabi]] soldiers of the famed \"Hodson's Horse\" regiment of the British Indian Army, pictured in the historical 1858 photograph.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP-->{{Circular reference|date=November 2017}} He was a descendant of Mirza Hakim Bey, after whom the Indian village Hakimpur, Gurdaspur District is named.\n* [[Mirza Aslam Baig]] a Former Chief of Army Staff of Pakistan.\n* [[Mirza Ghulam Murtaza]] was the chieftain of [[Qadian]] and a commander withn the [[Sikh Army]].\n* [[Mirza Kuchak Khan]] was a Persian revolutionary who led the Jungle Movement in the northern jungles of [[Gilan Province]].\n\n===Nobility===\n* [[Khan Mohammad Mridha Mosque|Khan Muhammad Mirza]], Architect during the Mughal Era.\n* [[Mirza Ali Behrouze Ispahani]],  Bangladeshi businessman from the [[Ispahani family]] and the chairman of [[M. M. Ispahani Limited]].\n* [[Mirza Hadi Baig]], Mughal nobleman from [[Samarkand]] who was granted 80 villages by [[Babur]].\n* [[Mirza Najaf Khan]], Indian Courtier and Commander in Chief of the Mughal Imperial Army.\n* [[Sikandar Mirza]], Armenian courtier within [[Akbar's Mughal Empire]]\n\n== Movies ==\n* ''[[Mirza \u2013 The Untold Story]]'' \u2013 Punjabi language Movie from India\n* [[Mirzya (film)|''Mirzya'' (film)]] \u2013 Hindi language Movie from India \n* ''[[Mirza Juuliet]]'' \u2013 Hindi language Movie from India\n\n== See also ==\n{{col-begin}}{{col-break}}\n* [[Rana (title)]]\n*[[Baig]], [[Bey]]\n*[[Beg Khan]]\n*[[Emir]]\n*[[Khanzada]]\n*[[Begzada]] {{nb10}}\n*[[Morza]]\n{{col-break}}\n*[[Mughal (tribe)]]\n*[[Muslim Rajput]]\n*[[Nawab]]\n*[[Shah#Shahzada|Shahzada]]\n*[[Sultanzada]]\n*[[Mirza Ghassemi]]\n*[[Sayyid]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n*''Life of a Mirza'' Chapter 7 (pg 225\u2013227) The 